fields.title: Secular Drift of Absorption Line Systems and the Cosmic Acceleration
fields.abstract: We request time to make high signal-to-noise observations of a sample of HI 21 cm absorption line systems that have been observed since 2004 by the GBT.  The goal is to confirm secular redshift drifts detected toward numerous absorbers over 20-30 year timescales while minimizing and controlling systematic errors.  The drifts have been identified by comparing GBT spectra to literature spectra from the pre-digital 1970's and 1980's, which raises concerns about systematic effects.  By re-observing these systems in 2012 with the exceptionally sensitive GBT, we will minimize systematic effects and confirm (or refute) these secular redshift drifts.  This project is a first step toward "real-time cosmology" whereby cosmological redshifts can be observed to change over human timescales due to cosmic acceleration.  This will be a model-independent direct way to probe the history of expansion and the nature of dark energy.  If the redshift drifts are confirmed, it will have a significant impact on --- and throw into question --- recent work on the cosmic evolution of physical constants (most of which relies on absorption line systems).  The total time request to re-observe 22 absorption line systems is 55 hours.

fields.title: Imaging the Thermal and Non-Thermal Corona of a Nearby Main Sequence Star
fields.abstract: Recent EVLA observations have confirmed the detection of the thermal coronae of two main sequence active M dwarfs at frequencies > 20 GHz. One of these stars is the well characterized flare star UV Ceti. We propose to conduct HSA [VLBA+GBT] observations of this star, switching between 8.4 and 23.8 GHz to produce a resolved image of the non-thermal (8.4 GHz) and thermal (23.8 GHz) corona of this star to establish the relative location of the parent plasma populations responsible for the emission. This will be the first resolved image of the thermal corona of a star other than the Sun and will provide crucial insight into the relationship between the thermal and non-thermal corona of active stars. Total time request is 12 hours.

fields.title: The Flow of Gas in the Milky Way Halo
fields.abstract: Gas flows into and out of the Milky Way are a crucial element in its evolution.  We wish to obtain high-quality 21cm spectra from the GBT in the direction of 42 QSOs and AGN lying behind high-velocity or intermediate-velocity HI clouds for which we have already measured UV absorption spectra or expect to obtain them in the near future.  The combined data set will allow us to investigate the abundances and ionization state of gas in the Milky Way halo, and discriminate between products of a galactic fountain and infall of low-metal gas.

fields.title: Revisiting the SiO masers in R Aqr
fields.abstract: We propose simultaneous full polarisation observations of the v=1 and v=2, J=1 to 0 SiO maser transitions in R Aqr. Fifteen years after the last VLBA monitoring of the SiO masers around R Aqr, it is the right time to revisit the star and study the masers in a more robust way. The uniform observations proposed and the addition of the v=2 transition, that will be studied in such detail for the first time, will create a complete dataset that can reveal the properties of the masing shell, its kinematics and rotation, and through its polarisation, the strength and geometry of the magnetic field. It will also reveal the effects (if any) of the approaching companion in the masing region.

fields.title: A2146:a bullet-like merging cluster with an exceptional Brightest Cluster Galaxy
fields.abstract: We have recently discovered the merging cluster A2146 (z=0.234). It is undergoing a spectacular merger in the plane of the sky, with a bullet-like structure. However, the brightest cluster galaxy in A2146 is exceptional since it is located some 40 kpc behind the X-ray surface brightness peak (galaxies should be collisionless and are expected to precede the hot X-ray gas in a merger). A possible explanation is that the galaxy has been "slingshotted" to its current location, a phenomena predicted by simulations. However, to test this theory, we need to constrain the kinematics of the galaxy along the plane of the sky. This can be done if we are able to detect radio jets, and if these jets have undergone some ram pressure stripping due to the movement of the galaxy through the dense gas. Current 8.4 GHz VLA observations clearly reveal that the galaxy has an elongated structure, but we are just barely resolving the jet at 8.4 GHz, and more resolved observations are needed. We therefore request 12 hours of VLBA observations in order to resolve the jet and derive the kinematics of the galaxy along the plane of the sky.

fields.title: What powers the kpc-scale radio lobes in Seyfert galaxies ?
fields.abstract: The exact origin of the kpc-scale radio outflows in Seyfert galaxies is still unclear. AGN jets and starburst superwinds are the two major contenders for lobe creation in Seyferts. We propose here for VLBA observations at 1.6 GHz of 12 Seyfert 2 galaxies belonging to the Extended 12 micron AGN sample. Our parsec-scale observations will determine the current jet directions in these sources and enable us to look at links between the AGN jet and the Seyfert lobes. We will examine if any "misaligned" jets can be explained by curved jets, as is suggested in NGC6764 & Mrk6, which could arise from jet precession or a rotating ISM. The Spitzer data will help determine the starburst contribution to the source energetics, while the Chandra data will examine the picture of "frustrated" jets and jet-ISM interaction in these galaxies. A detailed understanding of the radio structure on all scales is critical to our understanding the evolutionary state of these sources. Combining the new VLBA data on the youngest radio emitting material with the constraints provided by the larger scale radio, Chandra and Spitzer data will enable the role of jet precession and jet-cloud interactions to be investigated.

fields.title: VLBA monitoring of gamma-ray emitting NLS1 PMN J0948+0022
fields.abstract: We propose VLBA monitoring at 43 (and 22) GHz at the intervals of 1 month for 1 year for the radio-loud narrow-line Seyfert 1 (NLS1) galaxy PMN J0948+0022 (z=0.584), which is now of extreme interest since the Fermi/LAT discovered it in gamma-ray.  We are a pioneer group who have been investigating PMN J0948+0022 and other several radio-loud NLS1s as highly accreting small black hole systems using VLBA, since before the discovery by Fermi.   However, a bulk Lorentz factor still unknown for this source, although it is the most impact parameter to the modeling of overall SED.  The determination of jet kinematics in this NLS1 is eagerly desired in the astrophysical community.  Based on the Doppler factor determined by our previous VLBA studies, a superluminal motion of 6.8c-10c, corresponding to 0.31-0.46 mas/yr, is expected in a relativistic case; the VLBA at 43 GHz is the single route to this investigation.  A new large gamma-ray flare has been reported on June 2011 by Fermi/LAT (ATel#3429) and AGILE (ATel#3448); this winter or spring is a good time to start monitoring the emanated radio blob.

fields.title: Quasar/ULIRG Evolution STudy (QUEST): AGN Feedback in Merger Remnants
fields.abstract: As an element of the Quasar/ULIRG Evolution STudy (QUEST), a comprehensive multiwavelength program on local massive gas-rich mergers (ULIRGs & QSOs), we propose to obtain with the GBT HI 21-cm spectroscopic data of 19 ULIRGs and QSOs in the QUEST sample that do not have existing data.  The selected sources are fully coalesced mergers that are bolometrically dominated by an active nucleus.  The main goal of the program is to determine whether there is a fundamental link between ULIRGs, IR-excess QSOs, and optical QSOs.  Using GBT data, we wish to search for signatures of outflows (as indicated by X-ray, UV, and optical observations) along the merger sequence as suggested by recent theoretical work.  These observations will supplement data already obtained with HST, Spitzer, VLT/Keck, Chandra, XMM-Newton, and Herschel.

fields.title: The Pumping of the Nonmetastable Ammonia Maser in NGC 7538
fields.abstract:
We have recently renewed the study of the nonmetastable (J,K)=(9,6) ammonia (14NH3) in NGC7538.  Using the GBT and EVLA, we have observed several masers in the IRS1 region, including new masers in the kinematic clump near v_LSR=-56 km/s and masers redward of -54 km/s with no known associated clumps.

The pumping model proposed for nonmetastable ammonia suggests that, for a majority of excitation regimes, more than one J-rung in a K-ladder will show maser emission.  We propose to observe the appropriate transitions in the K=3 and K=6 ladders in order to diagnose the level populations and constrain the pumping regime.  This proposed experiment will not only provide the first test of the pumping model but will provide comprehensive level information suitable for constraining any population scheme.  In general, these observations will affect the interpretation of thermal and nonthermal emission from ammonia in star-forming regions.

Also, the appearance of new masers may be indicative of new conditions in the molecular clump at -56 km/s.  We also propose to observe the 15NH3 (3,3) masers for the first time in 20 years in order to detect any variability.

fields.title: Searching for Extended HI Structures Around Starburst dIm Galaxies NGC 4163/4214
fields.abstract: Dwarf galaxies are believed to be the building blocks of larger galaxies.  However, there are some new studies that indicate the dwarf galaxies observed today may have formed later, after the most massive galaxies coalesced.  Dwarf galaxy formation and evolution is, therefore, important for our understanding of cosmology.  If dwarf galaxies mimic their more massive counterparts, then starburst dwarfs may be present day merger remnants and provide information on the building block hypothesis.  The origins of starburst dwarf irregular (dIm) galaxies are not well known.  The role of interactions and mergers as mechanisms to create these systems has been hypothesized, but not well studied.  Therefore, we propose to use the GBT to search for extended HI structures around two starburst dIm galaxies, NGC 4163 and NGC 4214, in the Canes Venatici galaxy group.  These observations will add to a growing list of deep HI studies of the cosmological neighborhoods of dIm starburst galaxies and these data will be used in conjunction with hydrodynamical simulations.  Together, the simulations and observations will be used to determine the nature of dIm starburst systems.

fields.title: DCO+ as a tracer of molecular cloud age
fields.abstract:
Determining the age of clouds is an important open question which has some impact on our understanding of their dynamics and on star formation. We propose a new chemical test to reach this goal.
CO is present everywhere in dark clouds and reacts with H3+ to form HCO+, equally widespread. Similarly, deuterated H3+ isotopologues can form DCO+ but are absent when the cloud is young because ortho-H2 is still abundant from its formation on grains and destroys H2D+. We have shown that after a few million years, ortho-H2 being converted to para-H2, H2D+ and D2H+ should become abundant enough to form large quantities of DCO+ even without CO depletion. DCO+ should therefore appear all over the cloud. If it does not, the most probable cause is that the cloud is young enough to not have let DCO+ develop (Pagani et al., subm.). Today, DCO+ has not been searched with enough sensitivity outside prestellar cores where its presence is expected. We propose to make deep integrations in a few clouds away from their prestellar cores to bring stringent upper limits to the age of the clouds. The GBT is perfectly suited to this task.

fields.title: Unveiling Binary Supermassive Black Holes in Double-Peak Narrow-Line AGNs
fields.abstract: The proposed observations are a search for dual supermassive black holes (SMBHs) from a sample of double-peaked emission line galaxies identified in the SDSS.  Dual SMBHs are a prediction of hierarchical merging models for the growth of structure, and, at various points in their evolution, extremely tight binary SMBHs should emit gravitational waves that would be detectable by pulsar timing arrays or a future space-based interferometer.  While dual SMBHs are a natural explanation for double-peaked emission lines, they might also be generated by jets or outflows around single AGNs.  Optical and near-IR imaging programs are suggesting that dual AGN are not responsible for the majority of double-peaked emission line galaxies, but that a fraction of order 10% are likely to be dual AGN.  VLBA observations can easily probe to sub-kpc AGN separations, a difficult regime for optical and near-IR imaging programs, but barely two dozen double-peaked emission line galaxies have been observed with VLBI techniques.  This much larger sample should yield a few dual SMBHs (formally 7 +/- 3), if the fraction of radio-loud dual AGN is similar to that observed in the optical and near-IR imaging programs.

fields.title: Towards Precision Supermassive Black Hole Masses using Megamaser Disks
fields.abstract: We propose a new search for megamaser disks in galaxies, in which the mass of the central supermassive black hole can also be measured through optical/NIR observations using stellar-kinematical observations.  To date, stellar-dynamical measurements provide the foundation for the observed scaling relations between supermassive black holes and galaxies, indicating a fundamental evolutionary link between the two.  Using the < 10% precision supermassive black hole masses afforded by the megamaser disks, we hope to calibrate the stellar-dynamical measurements precisely.  This will be essential to understand the true scatter and systematics in the mass measurements.  We propose to observe 266 galaxies, which includes all galaxies with existing or feasible stellar-dynamical black hole masses.  We expect to detect three or more new megamaser disks for cross-comparison.  In addition, our survey will provide the first comprehensive study of the incidence of megamaser disks in systems with very low accretion rates.

fields.title: Helium RL detection from ELDWIM at 5 GHz
fields.abstract: The presence of a diffuse Extended Low Density Warm Ionized Medium(ELDWIM) within the inner Galaxy has been established by low frequency(<2GHz) Radio Recombination Line(RRL) observations(Lockman 1976 ; Mezger 1978 ; Ananatharamaiah 1985). This component is understood to have a typical electron density ne ~ 1-10 cm^-3 at electron temperatures  Te ~ 10^3-10^4 K. The ELDWIM is thought to extend from the Galactic center to ~13kpc and ~100pc above and below the Galactic plane. The recent estimated densities of ELDWIM are 1-10 cm-3(Murray & Rahaman 2010) with temperatures of the order of 3000-8000K. The origin, morphology and ionization mechanism of ELDWIM are uncertain. ELDWIM has been thought to be as a collection of evolved HII regions(Shaver 1976) or perhaps it forms the outer envelopes of HII regions(Anantharamaiah 1985).  However recently ELDWIM has been thought as a diffuse gas ionized by massive stellar clusters(Murray & Rahaman 2010). The proposed project aims at detecting helium line from ELDWIM in order to understand its ionization. He ionization potential(24.6 eV) is higher than H ionization potential(13.6 eV). Detection of He line strength indicates the ionization condition of ELDWIM.

fields.title: Discrepancy of the observed proper motions at different frequencies of M 87 jet
fields.abstract: We propose 11 epochs of VLBA observations at 15 GHz towards M 87 jet.  Surprisingly, the observed proper motions by VLBA at 15 and 43 GHz is different, even though both observed same region of the optically thin jet; VLBA observations at 43 GHz show superluminal jet (~ 2 c), while that at 15 GHz exhibit subluminal jet (< 0.05 c). The main purpose of this experiment is to conclude the discrepancy on this observed proper motions by choosing the proper time interval and epochs.  With this experiment, we probe the true jet velocity and its scale. Those are the most essential information to consider the acceleration of the relativistic jet.  In addition, understanding of this discrepancy would be important to comprehend the meaning of the VLBI knots themselves.

fields.title: Deuterated Ammonia as a Tool to Probe the Evolutionary Stage of Dense Cores
fields.abstract:
We propose to observe with the GBT a small sample of cores (20) in the nearby Perseus Molecular Cloud in NH2D and HCO+ isotopologues. These observations will make use of the new 4mm receiver under the shared risk program. The observation of the HCO+ isotopologues will allow us to determine the level of depletion for each core. The NH2D data will be combined with NH3 data to obtain the level of deuteration. Combining these observations we will establish NH2D, which until now has received little attention, as a tool to probe the evolutionary stage of dense cores.

These observations are expected to provide a new tool to determine the stage of evolution in dense cores that could allow a better/new use of the GBT and also ALMA band 3. This proposal will also showcase the new capabilities of the GBT 4mm receiver.

fields.title: CO(1-0) Observations of the  Herschel-ATLAS Sub-mm Galaxies in the NGP Field
fields.abstract: The wide-area H-ATLAS survey has uncovered a population of extremely bright submm galaxies (SMGs) at high-redshift.  The vast majority of these sources are amplified by lensing.  The GBT/Zpectrometer is an ideal instrument for identifying high-redshift galaxies for followup lensing studies, as highlighted by the 12 detections of CO(1-0) to date from the program.  The previous GBT/Zpectrometer observations concentrated on the three H-ATLAS equatorial fields.  The proposed observations of the North-Galactic-Pole Field (NGP) covers 150 sq-deg, which is more than all of the equatorial fields combined.  We propose to use Zpectrometer to obtain redshifts and to measure the masses of the cold molecular gas reservoirs for the 28 brightest H-ATLAS SMGs in the NGP (the final H-ATLAS field available to the GBT).  The GBT/Zpectrometer is currently the most efficient system for deriving redshifts and provides the key low-J CO(1-0) measurements that constrain the CO excitation and total molecular gas mass.  These observations will enable us ultimately to constrain the molecular gas mass function during the epoch of peak SMG activity at z=2--3.5.

fields.title: Test for the frustration scenario of radio sources hosted by BAL quasars
fields.abstract: Quasars with absorption troughs caused by an active galactic nucleus (AGN) wind from an accretion disk are called broad absorption line (BAL) quasars. One of plausible explanations to the fraction of BAL quasars is evolution scheme, where the ratio of BAL to non-BAL quasars is considered to result from duration of time when quasars possess the AGN wind. Compact radio morphology associated with BAL quasars is one of the basis for the evolution scheme. However, what makes the radio morphology compact is unclear and the compactness is not ready to be the conclusive evidence. Our previous study implied the frustration scenario of BAL quasars. Radio sources hosted by BAL quasars is confined by dense plasma and the nonthermal jet could be hard to evolve to larger one. In this case, the compactness does not indicate their youth stage, and thus one of the basis for the evolution scheme is overturned. To justify the frustration scenario, we propose VLBA observation for three BAL quasars. The aim of the observation is to derive spectral age and kinematic age. Comparing them, we can discuss whether our target sources are frustrated or at a young stage.

fields.title: Water maser in Compton-thick AGN
fields.abstract:
Water maser emission provides a unique way to map accretion disks and to estimate masses of the nuclear engines in Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN). An accurate analysis of the X-ray spectra of AGN instead allows us to estimate column densities along the line-of-sight, hence, their intrinsic luminosities that are a direct measure of the nuclear activity.
So far, AGN hosting H2O masers tend to show high column densities, often in the Compton-thick regime. Moreover, hints for a correlation between the X-ray and H2O maser luminosity have been recently found. However the lack of sizable and statistically complete samples of AGN with information on maser activity affects the confidence level of these results. Here, we propose to search for water maser emission, with the GBT, in a well defined sample of 34 Compton-thick AGN, carefully selected through a very efficient method based on the combination of infrared and 2-10 keV data.  With this sample we aim at studying the X-ray/maser connection in an homogeneous and statistically relevant way.

fields.title: Planetary Ephemeris Improvement through Spacecraft Astrometry
fields.abstract: The planetary ephemeris is an essential tool for studies of solar system dynamics, the prediction of occultations, tests of general relativity, and interplanetary spacecraft navigation. Previous VLBA astrometric observations of the Cassini spacecraft orbiting Saturn (BJ061 and BJ067) have provided the most accurate set of barycentric positions of Saturn currently available; this proposal seeks to continue the series of measurements for another two years. The Cassini mission will end in 2016, and represents a unique opportunity to obtain accurate position for Saturn over more than a quarter of its orbital period. The same observational approach can be used for the future Juno mission that will start orbiting Jupiter in mid-2016. Together, VLBA astrometry of Cassini and Juno will provide improved positions for both of the planets that dominate the dynamics of our solar system. In addition, this proposal requests three VLBA observations of current Mars orbiters to reduce the uncertainty in the orbit plane - the largest source of error in the ephemeris for Mars.

fields.title: Accurate trigonometric parallaxes of three near-Eddington neutron star accretors
fields.abstract: The 2006-2007 outburst of the transient neutron star low-mass X-ray binary (NS-LMXB) XTE J1701-462 showed for the first time that all NS-LMXB subclasses can be linked through a single parameter, the mass accretion rate. Based on a comparison with the shapes of the X-ray color-color tracks in XTE J1701-462 and the sequence in which they were observed, we have for the first time ranked a large number of NS-LMXBs as a function of what is presumably mass accretion rate. This ranking makes specific predictions about the relative X-ray luminosities of these sources. However, the lack of accurate distance estimates, especially at the high luminosity end of our ranking, prevents us from testing our proposed ranking. Here we propose VLBA observations of three near-Eddington accreting and radio bright NS-LMXBs, to obtain accurate trigonometric parallaxes.

fields.title: VLBA Geodesy/Astrometry Observations for 2012
fields.abstract:
The NASA/NRAO/USNO groups propose to continue to use the VLBA, and up
to ten additional stations, in a collaborative program of geodetic and
astrometric research during 2012. Six 24-hour days of observing time
are requested on the VLBA, spaced as evenly as is practical throughout
the year. We plan to use as many other stations as are proven capable
of VLBA/Mark IV/Mark 5 recording to enhance the network and provide
longer baselines but we will not exceed the capacity of the correlator at the time of the observations. The proposed observations will serve the collective needs of the three collaborating institutions. We will do repeated
imaging and evaluation of intrinsic source structure, evaluate and
maintain the long term stability of the International Celestial
Reference Frame, maintain the VLBA antennas in the VLBI terrestrial
reference frame, obtain the most accurate Earth rotation results, and
continue to provide a service to users who require high quality
astrometric positions for a few sources.

fields.title: Searching for Millisecond Pulsars in Extremely Low-Mass White Dwarf Binaries
fields.abstract: We request a total of 8.6 hours of GBT observations at 340 MHz of nine new extremely low-mass helium white dwarfs (ELM WDs) with masses ~0.17 Msun. No single-star evolutionary path is known for WDs with such low masses; instead, such objects are believed to evolve in binary systems with neutron stars (NSs), and many are found in millisecond pulsar (MSP) systems. With a >30% chance of having a companion with a mass >1.4 Msun, these ELM WDs may represent our best opportunity to uncover a system analogous to that of the MSP J1012+5307, one of the few WD/NS systems for which a NS mass has been measured. Confirming and characterizing a pulsar companion to any one of these ELM WDs would allow us to determine the properties of the two degenerate stars in this system--and in particular, the NS mass--to unprecedented precision.

fields.title: Correlating ELDWIM with HII regions
fields.abstract: The project aims to detect hydrogen and helium RLs from ELDWIM(Extended Low Density Warm Ionized Medium) using GBT in L-band. H and He RLs from ELDWIM(Lockman 1976 ; Mezger 1978 ; Shaver 1976; Ananatharamaiah 1985; Murray & Rahaman 2010) have already been observed. The origin, morphology and ionization mechanism of ELDWIM are uncertain. ELDWIM has been thought to be as a collection of evolved HII regions(Shaver 1976) or perhaps it forms the outer envelopes of HII regions(Anantharamaiah 1985). More recently it has been considered to be diffuse gas ionized by massive stellar clusters(Murray & Rahaman 2010). The proposed project aims to detect hydrogen and helium RLs from inner Galaxy(l < 21deg) using GBT and correlating the results with HII regions surrounding the line originating regions. GBT having a narrow beam(9') is ideal for sampling diffuse ionized gas  simultaneously avoiding HII regions within the beam.   A similar earlier observation with WSRT(L-band, 30') beam has shown the presence of diffuse ionized helium in the inner Galaxy. But due to the broad beam of WSRT it was not possible to avoid HII regions within the beam. The project aims at understanding the origin, morphology and ionization of ELDWIM.

fields.title: A New Water Fountain Survey Based on AKARI Color Criteria
fields.abstract: We propose to search for new candidates of "water fountains", which are objects associated with high velocity outflow traced by water maser emission, by introducing a new AKARI color criteria. Water fountains are suggested to be post-AGB stars in their final stage of stellar mass-loss, before entering the planetary nebula phase. By studying this transitional type of objects, we could learn about the mechanism of producing high velocity jets from late type stars, which contributes to the shaping of planetary nebulae as well as redistributing matters from the stars back to the interstellar space. We found that the water fountains have their own AKARI color characteristics comparing to other late type objects. In this project, we propose the relationship between the 9.7 micron silicate feature and the water fountains, and if we success, the results will certainly give the world a whole new angle in studying this type of rare object, and the new color criteria would increase the detection rate in future observations.

fields.title: PKS 2004-447: the first gamma-ray emitting young radio source?
fields.abstract:
We propose multifrequency VLBA observations of the gamma-ray emitting 
radio source PKS 2004-447. PKS 2004-447 has been included in the small sample of radio-loud Narrow-Line Seyfert 1s detected by Fermi-LAT during its first year of operation, but its classification is still controversial. In the radio band this object shows the typical properties of young radio sources: steep spectrum, no flux density variability, and compact structure. Archival L-band VLBA observations resolved the source into several components. 
With this proposal we ask for simultaneous observations at 1.4, 4.8, and 8.4 GHz to study the spectral index distribution across the source structure, crucial for determining whether the source is dominated either by lobes/hotspots as expected in a young radio source, or by core-jets, as in blazar. If the genuine youth of the source is confirmed, PKS 2004-447 will be the first young radio source detected in gamma rays, providing an unprecedented chance to study the physical mechanisms at work up in this class of sources to the highest energies.

fields.title: Phase-referencing measurements of positional shifts in ultra-compact AGN cores
fields.abstract: Accurate alignment of the optical reference frame to be established by GAIA with the VLBI based International Celestial Reference Frame (ICRF) requires good understanding of the positional discrepancies of the reference objects used for the alignment. Nuclear opacity is expected to cause offsets (core shifts) of order of 0.1 mas between the radio and optical positions of the reference sources. Measuring these core shifts at several radio frequencies is needed for improving the feasibility and accuracy of the reference frame alignment. The compactness of the ICRF objects requires relative astrometry for measuring the core shifts, however there are no established methods and approaches for such measurements. We have designed a comprehensive project aimed at testing several potential methods for core shift measurements using relative astrometry, and we propose to carry out such tests with the VLBA at 5 and 15 GHz, requiring the total of 12 hours of observing time. These observations will provide crucial input for devising an optimal approach for the radio-optical reference frame alignment.

fields.title: DCO+ as a tracer of CO depletion in prestellar cores
fields.abstract: Prestellar cores are on the roadmap of star formation in dark clouds. Until the arrival of bolometers they were impossible to find because of local molecular depletion making them unconspicuous to molecular gas surveys, especially those based on CO isotopologues. CO depletion is witnessed in most prestellar cores but the amount of depletion, the mechanisms of both depletion and desorption are not well-understood. The major problem is that the depleted CO region is weakly emitting and therefore is masked by the undepleted external layer strong emission. However, the presence of CO can be derived from the DCO+ emission which usually peaks close to the dust peak. Though the relation between the two species is straightforward, the quantification of CO is not, and we propose a strategy to solve this problem based on the comparison of the DCO+/HCO+ profile with the N2D+/N2H+ profile. With this approach, we propose to observe DCO+ along a strip across the L183 core and map the very inner part in all three DCO+, N2D+ and N2H+ 1-0 transitions to follow the depletion up to the highest densities in the prestellar core. The derived CO profile will bring constraints to the depletion phenomenon.

fields.title: High sensitivity continuous observation of Sgr A* for investigating QPOs
fields.abstract: We found conspicuous patterned changes of the structure with P = 16.8, 22.2, 31.4, 56.4 min. The first two periods show a rotating one-arm structure, while the P =31.4 min shows a rotating 3-arm structure, as if viewed edge-on. Spatial distributions of the oscillation periods suggest that the disk of Sgr A* is roughly edge-on. Presumably, the observed VLBI images of Sgr A* at 43 GHz retain several features of the black hole accretion disk of Sgr A* in spite of being obscured and broadened by scattering of surrounding plasma. We devised two methods. One is to use the data of long baselines including HN, SC and MK using CALIB-task carefully. The second method is slit-modulation-imaging (SMI) which is a way of examining the existence of the periodic structural change free from u-v sampling differences between snap shot maps. However, this result is now under discussion due to difficulties of analyzing and treatment of data. Therefore, we wish to have 8-hours 2-epoch (3 mm and 7 mm) observations of Sgr A* continuously to confirm the detection of QPOs without doubt.

fields.title: Search for Binary AGNs  in Radio Quasars with Double Absorption Lines
fields.abstract: The six sources we proposed show double peaked Mg II  absorption lines, and 3/6 high redshift sources also show double peaked C IV absorption lines. One special spectra of the six sources show various velocity offsets between double absorption lines and double emission lines, which we re-observed with MMT(6.5m). This source is likely in the early stage of merger, with two galaxies interacting and moving around each other. The double-peaked emission lines are likely from the binary AGNs locating in two host galaxies, and the double absorption lines may come from two host galaxies. So, similarly, all the six double peaked Mg II  absorption lines the most likely come from host galaxies. The proposed high spatial resolution radio observations can help us to test the merger and/or binary AGN scenario. We propose to observe the 6 sources with VLBA for 15 hours at 1.4 GHz, with 4 of them requiring using phase-referencing technique.

fields.title: W43 and the Warm Ionised Medium
fields.abstract: W43 is one of the most massive star forming regions in the Galaxy.  It is located at the end of the Galactic bar, where we expect to see colliding gas flows and, as a result, strong star formation. As part of the GBT HII Region Discovery Survey (HRDS), we discovered that nearly all HII regions within one degree of W43 have two velocity components, one near 50 km/s and one near 90 km/s (the latter is close to the velocity of W43).  The most likely explanation is that we detected the warm ionised medium (WIM).  It is unclear however which velocity component is from the WIM and which comes from the compact HRDS sources.  We propose to create a one square degree map the W43 region in recombination line emission at C-band.  This will allow us to determine which component is from the WIM, as well as the spatial extent and strength of the WIM in this direction.  These observations will provide key insight into the nature of the WIM and its connection with massive star formation regions.

fields.title: Arecibo-GBT 70-cm Targeted Lunar Radar Mapping
fields.abstract: We request 24 hours of Arecibo-GBT time to acquire targeted 70-cm wavelength, dual-polarization radar backscatter maps of the Moon. The new observations achieve 200-m spatial resolution, revealing details of rugged lava flows buried beneath the dusty soil of the vast lunar volcanic plains. The discovery of these rough flows is provoking a re-examination of our understanding of lunar volcanic processes, and the possible roles of volatiles on magma properties. Our new maps will extend the search for hidden rugged flows across all of the major nearside plains.

fields.title: Multifrequency VLBA observations of faint high frequency peakers
fields.abstract:
We propose simultaneous multifrequency VLBA observations of three high
frequency peaking radio sources to constrain their physical
properties. In the framework of evolutionary models, radio sources
whose synchrotron spectral peak occurs at frequencies above a few GHz
should represent the population of very young objects with ages of a
few hundred years. Although they are thought to be the progenitors of
the extended kpc-scale radio galaxies, their evolutionary path seems
much more complicated. Recent works suggest that a fraction of
young radio sources are short-lived objects whose evolution depends 
on their luminosity. The aim of this proposal is to derive the initial
conditions in which the radio emission starts to evolve in order to
draw a reliable picture of the fate of young radio sources.

fields.title: Constraining Stellar and Galactic Chemical Evolution with 3-Helium Abundances
fields.abstract: Our 140-Foot 3-Helium experiment led to "The 3-He Problem" whereby HII region abundances do not show the 3-He enrichment expected from standard stellar nucleosynthesis.  This conundrum stimulated a new generation of stellar evolution and Galactic Chemical Evolution (GCE) models that now include rotational and thermohaline instabilities. All current GCE models predict a 3-He abundance gradient across the Galactic disk.  Unfortunately the errors in the derived 140-Foot 3-He abundances are too large to test the new models.  We shall use the GBT to derive 3-He abundances that can give robust GCE constraints.  This requires an HII region sample that spans the Galactic disk and for which precise line parameters, accurate abundances, and good error estimates can be had.  Here we propose a Filler Project to begin this effort, building on our experience with our 11A_043 Filler Project which uses a spectrometer configuration that contains 46 different radio recombination lines simultaneously.  These, together with continuum measurements, can be used to construct the numerical models needed to derive accurate 3-He abundances.  Our first step will be to identify the HII region sample that can give the most accurate 3-He abundances.

fields.title: OH Zeeman Observations in GMCs and OH survey
fields.abstract: We propose 18 cm OH Zeeman observations towards the Orion A and Taurus Molecular Clouds in non-core positions. Zeeman observations have been conducted in the past toward GMC cores. However, the cores hold only a small fraction of the mass. In this study we wish to explore the role of magnetic fields in GMCs as a whole.  To do so, we will use Zeeman effect data to determine the mass-to-flux ratios of GMCs.  Are such clouds magnetically subcritical or supercritical?  We also propose to survey OH lines in GMCs to identify future Zeeman targets.  GBT observations will be part of a comprehensive program to study magnetic fields in GMCs as a whole.  This program has already consumed a significant amount of observing time at Arecibo.

fields.title: Hierachical Fragmentation Processes within the Orion Molecular Cloud
fields.abstract: Whether and how parsec-scale filaments will fragment and how these processes will affect localized star formation, is crucial to understand the initial condition and evolutionary processes of embedded star clusters within the filaments. In order to observationally study this, we are initiating a large-scale study that consists of imaging observations in the 7 mm continuum emission toward the Orion molecular filaments. Our observations with the EVLA/D+C arrays have being successfully imaging spatial distributions of compact continuum sources (i.e., protostellar and prestellar sources) within the pc-scale filaments.  However, the EVLA observations do not have the sensitivity for the extended emission (>32") due to the missing short spacing information. In order to obtain the extended emission, we propose to perform imaging observations using the GBT in the Q-band continuum emission. Our goals of the GBT+EVLA project are to (i) complete the census of star formation within the filaments including both prestellar and protostellar populations without missing flux, (ii) investigate hierarchical filamentary structures, which is likely related to multi-scale fragmentation processes, (iii) reveal how the multi-scale fragmentation and associated star formation propagate along the OMC filaments.

fields.title: Characterizing a New Population of Protostars in Orion Identified by Herschel
fields.abstract: We propose to use the GBT to characterize a population of 78 protostars in Orion, newly identified from sensitive 70 micron images taken with the Herschel Space Observatory as part of the Herschel Orion Protostar Survey (HOPS). The identification of these previously unknown protostars, the PACS Bright Red Sources (PBRS), is one of the biggest results from Herschel and we must now characterize these systems in relation to the known protostars in Orion. These protostars could represent a very brief phase of evolution shortly after collapse; the large, mostly complete sample of protostars in Orion enables us to identify possibly brief evolutionary phases. To characterize these systems, we propose to observe all 78 systems in the ammonia (1,1), (2,2), and (3,3) lines to determine kinetic temperatures and ammonia column densities. These data will be directly compared with the completed Di Francesco et al. survey of 280 HOPS protostars in Orion. Furthermore, to characterize the 9 reddest or coldest systems, we propose to observe the N2D+ and N2H+ ratio by observing the (J=1-0) lines with the new W-band receiver. Protostellar envelopes that have formed very recently are expected to have very high N2D+/N2H+ ratios.

fields.title: SiO Masers in the Galactic Center:  Probing the Metric and General Relativity
fields.abstract: We propose to search for circumstellar SiO masers close to the massive black hole in the Galactic Center. Position and velocity tracking of maser-emitting stars within ~0.1 pc of Sag A* will provide multiple direct probes of the metric (stellar motion plus light propagation) and will enable numerous tests of general relativity not possible even with binary pulsars. If SiO maser-emitting stars are identified close to Sag A* with the GBT, then subsequent interferometric Doppler and proper motion tracking can test the equivalence principle, the "no-hair" theorem of black holes, and frame-dragging. While previous surveys for low-velocity Galactic Center masers have been done, the proposed survey will be 10 times more sensitive, and will have 100 times the bandwidth; it will be the first survey able to detect high velocity stars deep in the gravitational potential of the central black hole. Our maser survey requires 2 hours of on-source integration in four tunings and a total of 12 hours of observing time.

fields.title: The incidence and evolution of AGN in 2865 COSMOS radio sources
fields.abstract:
VLBI observations of AGN traditionally target carefully selected samples, to study particular aspects of their properties and surroundings. In contrast, we propose here to image all 2865 radio objects found in the VLA-COSMOS survey, using the new correlation and calibration techniques that we have developed in previous wide-field VLBI observations. Since all known radio emitters in the COSMOS 2 sq-deg field are targeted, without other selection applied, we will build, for the first time, a sample of flux-limited, VLBI-detected objects in a large variety of galaxies.

The main scientific goal of this project is to study the incidence and impact of radio-emitting AGN. We will (i) determine which objects host compact cores; (ii) determine how these objects affect the star formation in their host galaxies; and (iii) investigate the changes in accretion modes as a function of redshift. Furthermore, we anticipate significant input for additional, unexpected use cases of the survey data and input for follow-up observations. The COSMOS field unprecedented optical, IR, X-ray, and spectroscopic coverage, and therefore is the ideal place for our project.

fields.title: Limits on the position wander of Mrk 501 core at 7 mm
fields.abstract: We propose the observation towards blazar Mrk 501 at 7 mm. To investigate the location of the suppermassive black-hole powering AGN jets is so important that the location is crucial to jet formation mechanism. We predict that blazar-core position change can be detected with VLBI if the radio core is located more than 1 pc from the central black-hole. Blazar-core astrometry is a promising way to test the core position change and limit core location from the black hole.

fields.title: Multi-Frequency Astrometry of the Core Shift due to Free-Free Absroption
fields.abstract: It is well known that the positions of AGN cores are observed to be frequency-dependent due to optically thickness of free-free absorption (FFA) and/or synchrotron self absorption (SSA).Our previous multi-frequency VLBA phase-referencing for NGC 4261 at 1.4-43 GHz revealed the position of central black hole very precisely, the radial profile of accreting FFA plasma, and the FFA-induced core shifts. We also propose the observations of nearby radio galaxies, Cyg A, 3C 84 and Cen A using the same method. The aim is to reveal the structure of plasma gas around the super-massive black holes by determining core position shifts as a function of the frequency and then by accurately piling up multi-frequency images.  We request total observing time about 36 hours (12 hours x 3  target) for phase-referencing at 1.4-43 GHz. The expected amount of core shifts for each target and the error budget for the measurements of core positions are presented in this proposal.

fields.title: High precision absolute pulsar astrometry for the Parkes Pular Timing Array
fields.abstract:
This proposal is part of the campaign to detect gravitational waves using the Parkes Pulsar Timing Array (PPTA).  We will measure the absolute positions and proper motions with VLBI for a number of pulsars from the PPTA, which are not in current astrometric programs. These pulsars include the more difficult targets, being weak or with low declinations. Therefore we will use the full range of methods to compensate for ionospheric errors which provide improved astrometry.  In particular, to use multiple calibrators to solve for a 2D measurement of the residuals, which we have been developing to address the issues of high accuracy astrometry at low frequencies.

We will a) derive independent accurate absolute positions for PPTA targets aiding in the search for Gravitational Waves, b) apply multi-source calibration to astrometry and extend it to targets which have been considered too difficult, c) compare this approach to the established ones, and d) combine all approaches to push to new levels of accuracy with the VLBA and with future instruments at the low frequency regime.

fields.title: Measuring the Distance to the Galactic Center: Parallax of SgrA*
fields.abstract: This proposal describes a program to carry out three preliminary epochs of astrometric observations designed to measure the parallax of SgrA*, the super massive black hole candidate at the Galactic Center.  The proposed project builds on previous VLBA observations by our group, in which we used prototype versions of the new digital VLBI backends that are currently being deployed as part of the High Sensitivity Upgrade for the VLBA.  Now, with the addition of the GBT and dynamic scheduling made possible by full integration of the new backends and recorders, it should be possible to obtain a geometric distance to SgrA* to better than 4% uncertainty.  This precision measurement will impact a number of different fields in astronomy.  A successful effort will lead to independent recalibration of the cosmic distance ladder, refinement of mass estimates of the SgrA* black hole, and re-estimation of key parameters of Milky Way structure including masses of molecular clouds, ages of young stars, location of spiral arms and distances to massive star forming regions.

fields.title: Kinetic Temperature in Starburst Galaxies
fields.abstract: Studies of the distribution of CO emission in external galaxies have pointed to the presence of large quantities of dense molecular material in these objects.  These studies have yielded detailed pictures of the molecular mass in many external galaxies.  Because the CO emission from external galaxies is dominated by radiative transfer effects, such as high optical depth, it is not a reliable monitor of the physical conditions which give rise to star formation in these systems. Furthermore, many molecules used to trace the molecular mass in external galaxies, including CO, HCN, HCO+, CS, CH3OH, and C3H2, suffer from a coupled sensitivity to the kinetic temperature and spatial density, making them degenerately sensitive to high or low spatial densities and kinetic temperatures. Results from a survey of galaxies using the GBT (Mangum etal (2008a,2011)) have shown that H2CO is a reliable and accurate density probe for extragalactic environments where the kinetic temperature is known. Using the unique sensitivities to kinetic temperature and spatial density afforded by the inversion transitions of NH3, we propose to continue our characterization of the dense gas in starburst galaxies by measuring the kinetic temperature in a sample of galaxies selected for their high infrared luminosity.

fields.title: Water vs. OH maser emission: brotherhood or mutual exclusion?
fields.abstract: A thorough analysis of the connection between extragalactic maser emission from water and OH is affected by the low number of objects searched for both transitions. Our preliminary study indicates that, as expected, low-luminosity maser emission from both molecular species can indeed be present in the same object, most likely because of the association of such emission with star formation processes. Differently, only one case, that of Arp299, is found to host megamaser emission from both molecules. Here we propose to observe all the northern water maser galaxies reported so far in a search for 1.6-GHz OH maser emission. Our study will allow us to determine, on a firm statistical bases, the interplay between the occurrence of maser emission from the two species. Furthermore, it will likely provide a large number of new OH maser detections to be followed up through interferometric measurements in order to derive relevant information on positions and excitation conditions, both in kilomaser SF-related and megamaser AGN-related sources. This study may constitute a test bed to critically probe the Unified Scheme for AGN.

fields.title: Molecular Gas Observations of Luminous Infrared Galaxies in GOALS
fields.abstract:
Luminous infrared galaxies (LIRGs: L_IR > 10^11 L_sun) are primarily interacting or merging disk galaxies undergoing enhanced star formation and Active Galactic Nuclei (AGN) activity, possibly triggered as the objects transform into massive S0 and elliptical merger remnants. We are presently engaged in a multi-wavelength campaign called the Great Observatories All Sky LIRG Survey (GOALS) designed to assess the star formation and AGN properties of a complete sample of LIRGs from the IRAS Revised Bright Galaxy Sample. We propose a pilot study making use of the W-band 4mm receiver on the GBT to observe HCN and HCO+ in 18 GOALS LIRGs visible from Green Bank. These observations will be combined with IR measures of luminosity and AGN/starburst strengths to assess the robustness of mm lines as AGN/starburst diagnostics (HCN/HCO+) or star formation rate indicators (L'_HCN). Assessing the usefulness of these 
lines as potential diagnostics is a high priority in the age of ALMA, as distant submm-detected galaxies may be too faint to observe with diagnostic optical or near-IR lines. The data will also provide a much needed calibration of amount of line emission resolved out by interferometric observations of LIRGs.

fields.title: GBT NH3 and C2S observations of Planck cold clumps
fields.abstract: We propose ammonia and CCS observations for a sample of 80 cold clumps recently detected by Planck. The sample has been identified by using a Monte Carlo approach, i.e. by randomly sampling - in longitude, latitude and mass - the parental distribution of sources in the publicly available Planck Early Cold Clumps Catalog (ECC).  Given the statistical nature of the selected sample, we anticipate that the proposed observations will allow us at once to  individually characterize the sources in the sample, as well as to evidence global correlations of the parameters constrained by the observations (column densities, gas temperatures, evolutionary stage, etc.) with the environment.

fields.title: An H I 21-cm Survey of Active Galaxies Detected in the Very Hard X-rays
fields.abstract: We request an HI emission line survey of a unique sample of local, active galactic nuclei galaxies detected in the very hard X-ray band with the Swift Gamma-ray Burst satellite's all-sky survey.  Selection of AGN in the very hard X-rays is both less biased with respect to obscuration than optical/UV/soft X-ray bands and unambiguous in that the very hard X-rays are produced purely from the AGN, with no star formation contribution.  Additionally, our very hard X-ray sample is well-studied in multiple wavelengths (with published analyses of optical and X-ray spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy, and optical imaging); but is missing uniform coverage at the longer wavebands.  We propose an HI emission line survey of the host galaxy atomic gas to (1) determine systemic velocities, allowing us to accurately determine outflow velocities in our optical/UV/X-ray spectroscopy, (2) look for differences in the host galaxy gas content between X-ray unobscured and X-ray obscured AGN, and (3) provide an important comparison sample of pure AGN host properties for recent studies of starburst and/or AGN driven LIRGs.  We request 40 hours to observe 95 active galaxies.

fields.title: Dust Formation in the Atmospheres of AGB Stars
fields.abstract:
We propose to make SiO maser observations of AGB stars
coordinated with infrared interferometric
measurements at 11 micron with the Berkeley ISI interferometer.
The 11 micron observations are especially sensitive to the inner layer
of hot dust. 
This combination of observations should determine the relationship of
the SiO mazing region to that of dust formation, in particular, the
presence of dust interior to the SiO masing region.

fields.title: Confirmation of Interstellar CH2D+, Cornerstone of Hydrocarbon Chemistry
fields.abstract: CH3+ is a cornerstone molecule in interstellar chemistry. However, its symmetry renders it unobservable at radio wavelengths. One must rely on detection of its rare isotopomer CH2D+ to secure a measurement of its abundance . Detection of CH2D+ is challenging. As a light molecule, energy levels are widely spaced and transitions few, rendering both laboratory and astronomical measurement difficult. Unfortunately the molecule reacts with H2, which ensures all forms of CH3+ are low in abundance. Until recently precise measurements of the spectrum were not available. However, Amano (2010) has succeeded in accurately measuring the CH2D+ spectrum. Lis etal (2009) reported candidate detections of two lines, the frequencies of which agree very well with Amano's predictions. Maps made with the IRAM-30m support the identification of the candidate lines with CH2D+. A two-line detection in OMC1 however, remains insecure. We propose to observe a third line at 67.3 GHz using the new 4mm system on the GBT in order to more firmly establish our measurement of interstellar CH2D+. We will: 1) Identify CH2D+ at 67GHz 2) Constrain excitation and measure column density. 3) Model the chemistry which then predicts fractionation and the abundance of unobservable CH3+.

fields.title: Completing a Water Maser Survey of Active Black Holes in the Local Universe
fields.abstract: We propose to complete a survey for water maser lines in a large distance-limited radio-selected sample of nearby galaxies. The ultimate goal is to identify cases of water maser disks that enable the measurement of central black hole masses. Our selection method includes galaxies where the black hole mass may not obey the usual scaling with stellar bulge mass or velocity dispersion and may lead or lag the galaxy. We include galaxies and black holes likely to be in transition, such as major galaxy mergers spanning the merging sequence, starburst dwarf galaxies, various types of AGN (including radio-loud), and galaxy cluster members. We will include in the observations the first four inversion lines of ammonia for molecular gas temperature measurements, a radio recombination line to diagnose atomic gas conditions, and an excited OH line associated with radio jets.  Observation of the remaining 215-galaxy sample for 10 minutes apiece --- plus special observations of IIZw40 and IC 750 --- requires 57.5 hours including overhead. We expect to detect a few new black hole-associated water masers in this survey (one very bright maser disk candidate has already been discovered in IC 750 in program GBT 11A-056).

fields.title: Mapping magnetic fields in Young Stellar Objects: A Case Study of HD 283447
fields.abstract: The magnetic fields of young stellar objects (YSO) are key in transporting both mass and angular momentum from the protostellar object. Yet the strength and structure of these fields is poorly known. The embeded nature of these objects, along with the size scale of their non-thermal emitting regions, makes it difficult to measure and map their corresponding fields.  While there are several indirect techniques for studying YSO fields, the only direct technique is polarization sensitive, high angular resolution VLBI observations. In the following we propose a case study of HD 283447, a fundamental YSO multiple star. With multi-epoch imaging of this object we will be able to characterize both the magnetic field topology as well as the interaction between its components. This project will inform a larger VLBI study of YSO magnetic fields.

fields.title: VLBI observations Will Reveal the Nature of Tidal Disruption Event, Sw 1644+573
fields.abstract: The recent gamma-ray transient, Sw J164449.3+573451, is a unique event in the history of high energy surveys.  We have discovered a bright long-wavelength counterpart at radio and mm-bands and have since undertaken a monitoring campaign that extends across the electromagnetic spectrum. First VLBI observations were already successfully obtained and resulted in clear detections with limits on the size and proper motion of the source. The combination of high resolution radio interferometry with our on-going multi-wavelength campaign provides the first opportunity to shed light on transient accretion onto a supermassive black hole.

fields.title: Do the Properties of Star-Forming Dense Gas vary across the Galactic Disk?
fields.abstract: We proposed pointed K-band spectroscopy of 314 millimeter continuum sources in the outer Galaxy.   We request shared-risk use of the new VEGAS spectrometer to observe eight spectral lines simultaneously.  The eight species include three lines of ammonia which provides direct diagnostics of gas properties, water masers and C2S emission as measures of evolutionary state, and three recombination lines as measurements of ionized gas from high-mass star formation.  Parallel work in the inner Galaxy using the GBT revealed that dense gas clumps in that region were surprisingly uniform, making a tentative connection to uniformity of the large-scale star formation laws observed in other galaxies.  Using limited data from the outer Galaxy, it appears that clumps there are warmer and chemically poor, differing markedly from their inner Galaxy analogues.  We propose for additional observations to verify this suggestive difference in dense gas properties.  Confirming such a difference would necessitate different treatment of star-formation laws in metal-poor systems and/or the outer regions of other galaxies.

fields.title: Resolving the Synchrotron Emission from Colliding Magnetospheres
fields.abstract: We propose to image the quasi-periodic flare emission from the DQ Tau spectroscopic binary. This non-thermal activity is attributed to synchrotron radiation initiated by a brief collision of the stellar magnetospheres (R ~ 5 Rstar) when the stars approach a minimum separation of 8 Rstar. Our goals are: 1) to image the emission region at 3.6 cm with ~2 mas resolution (about 0.3 AU linear resolution), and 2) to measure (with at least 50 microarcsecond accuracy --- 1 Rstar) the relative centroid of the synchrotron emission for the roughly 8-hour period when the source is above the horizon at most VLBA antennas. These proposed VLBA observations will provide direct constraints on the physical size of the magnetic loops trapping the high-energy electron population. To date, these loop sizes have only been inferred from unresolved millimeter and X-ray data. Imaging and tracking the emission will allow us to distinguish between single-star reconnection events, star-disk interactions, collisions of the fields in the two stellar jets, ionized stellar winds or other extended structures, which are all possible mechanisms to generate the synchrotron emission.

fields.title: MUGS: a Pilot MUSTANG Galactic Plane Survey
fields.abstract: The Galactic plane has been surveyed extensively at radio and millimeter and shorter wavelengths, but there are currently no high angular resolution, large area surveys of the galaxy between 5 and 270 GHz. Such a survey is essential in order to form a complete and unbiased view of the physical conditions in the star forming regions of our Galaxy. We propose a pilot 21 deg^2 survey in the 3.3mm continuum with MUSTANG on the GBT.

fields.title: Extension Request for 12.6-cm Radar Mapping of the Nearside of the Moon
fields.abstract: We are requesting an extension for one year (through January, 2013) of time allocated (GBT09C-045) to complete a radar map of the lunar near side at 12.6-cm wavelength. This extension is necessary due to a hiatus in availability of the Arecibo radar from February 2010 to the present. The current transmitter problem is being repaired, and we expect to resume mapping in early 2012.

fields.title: Locating the TeV Emission Region in M87, IV.
fields.abstract: An understanding of the physics of the TeV emission in AGN and of the implications of that emission for the nature of the emitting region requires knowing the location, which cannot be determined with adequate accuracy by the atmospheric Cerenkov telescopes.  We are attempting to relate flaring in the TeV emission from M87 to activity at other wavebands where higher resolution instruments can obtain better positions.  M87, with a very large black hole, relative proximity, and occasional TeV flaring events, is arguably the best source for such studies.  One of the three episodes of TeV flaring observed so far corresponded to a flare observed at 43 GHz with the VLBA in 2008.  Results indicated a location less than about a hundred Schwarzschild Radii from the black hole.  But was the temporal coincidence fortuitous?  The other two, somewhat different, events gave more ambiguous results including no radio increase in 2010.  Here we request VLBA 43 GHz observations of M87 in the event of a high energy trigger to try to make sense of this source.  The data will also contribute to long term studies of the structure of the M87 jet and the relative transverse motions of M87 and M84.

fields.title: VLBA Observations toward Transient "Water Fountain" Candidate IRAS 19069+0916
fields.abstract: We propose OH and H2O maser observations toward IRAS 19069+0916 which shows a blue-shifted one-side "water fountain" feature at particular epochs. With these observations, we want to confirm its classification as a transient "water fountain" and determine the dynamical center and inclination (with respect to line of sight) of the H2O maser jet and/or outflow. We also expect to confirm that the transient "water fountain" source, IRAS 19069+0916 is at an earliest evolutionary stage of water fountain sources in just operating and dimming the "water fountain" features.

fields.title: Dynamical Mass Measurement of A Brown Dwarf Binary System
fields.abstract: Direct mass measurement of brown dwarfs is critical for empirically constraining substellar evolutionary models. Dynamical mass measurement campaigns are ongoing and involve AO-assisted astrometric observations with 8-10m class telescopes and the HST. These data is used to determine the relative orbital parameters and hence total mass for the system. However, the absence of absolute orbital parameters precludes establishing the masses of the individual components of the system. We have detected the secondary component of the tight binary brown dwarf system 2MASS J07464256+2000321 in VLBI observations in March 2010. These results confirm that VLBI observations can be used to obtain the absolute orbit of the secondary component of this binary system, thereby confirming the mass of the individual components of the system to an accuracy of ~1%, the first time the has been achieved for brown dwarfs. We request 35 hours of HSA observations over the period of three years to determine the absolute orbital parameters for this system. Total time request is 35 hours.

fields.title: Deep searches for young pulsars in two globular clusters
fields.abstract: We request 18 hr to carry out full-transit observations of the globular clusters NGC 6342 and M69 using the GBT at L-band.  These observations would provide an order of magnitude improvement in sensitivity over previous searches of these clusters and allow us to: (a) confirm or refute the association of PSR B1718-19 with NGC 6342; (b) test a recent hypothesis that high metallicity clusters such as these two harbor young neutron stars; (c) search for new recycled pulsars in both clusters.

fields.title: Large angle pulsar lensing from electron clouds
fields.abstract:
We propose to use the GUPPI pulsar data recorder and the newly
developed technique of cyclic spectroscopy to detect faint secondary
pulsar images from large scattering angles. These observations will
constrain the properties and population of Galactic refractive lenses,
responsible for Extreme Scattering Events (ESEs). There are no
constraints on the scheduling epoch. This project is a
perfect application for the cyclic spectroscopy technique to constrain
the plasma lens electron distribution, as well as the population and
distribution of the lenses in the Galaxy. We are requesting a total
time of 9-h (6-h on source and up to 3-h for overheads) to observe 12
pulsars using the GBT at L-band. The data will be used for the PhD
thesis of the PI.

fields.title: GBT-GMRT P-band VLBI at high S/N
fields.abstract: We explore GBT-GMRT P-band VLBI interferometry on PSR B0329+54.  This pulsar provides signal-to-noise larger than 1 during the peak flux, allowing a direct measurement of the voltage transfer function.  GUPPI and GSB allow 8 bit recording, opening up a new window of VLBI imaging.  In the long term, this could enable direct measurement of pulsar distances, emission sizes, and ISM properties.  The exploratory time has already been approved by GMRT

fields.title: Are long-period, high-B radio pulsars progenitors of Isolated Neutron Stars?
fields.abstract:
The 7 Isolated Neutron Stars intrigue both because of the hope of
determining neutron-star parameters and because of their large
inferred population.  Regarding the latter, from timing we found
remarkably similar field strengths and consistently long
characteristic ages, suggestive of initially stronger fields that
decayed, a result reproduced theoretically. There should then be
slowly rotating, strong-field progenitors heated by field decay.  We
have identified such a pulsar (likely among the closest) with X-ray
observations, and it now presents an opportunity for in-depth studies
that link the radio-loud and radio-quiet populations.  In particular,
here we propose for a short EVLA observation to image the field and
pave the way for a future astrometric campaign to measure the
kinematic age and study the suitability for a VLBA parallax
measurement, and for GBT polarimetric timing observations to
determine the pulsar's ephemeris and constrain its emitting geometry.
These will be combined with present and future X-ray data to
understand the role that magnetic-field decay has played both in this
single object and in the population as a whole.

fields.title: A Search for Offset Black Holes in Nearby Galaxies: Lowering the Detection Limit
fields.abstract:
Nearly all galaxy bulges contain supermassive black holes (SMBHs), so galaxy assembly by hierarchical merging should produce wide pairs of slowly inspiraling SMBHs that either "stall" as tight binaries with a few pc separation or merge and are kicked away from the galaxy nucleus by anisotropic gravitational radiation.  We are making a systematic X-band VLBA search (large program BC 196) for off-nuclear inspiraling or recoiling SMBHs and for tight SMBH pairs in a complete sample of 923 nearby (D ~ 200 Mpc) 2MASS galaxies containing NVSS radio sources stronger than 100 mJy.  This survey simultaneously addresses three scientific problems: (1) SMBH/galaxy co-evolution implied by the SMBH/bulge mass correlation, (2) the merger-tree theory of SMBH evolution, and (3) the expected contribution of merging SMBH binaries to the gravitational-wave background sought by LISA and the NANOGrav pulsar timing experiment.  We have already observed most of this sample and our VLBA detection rate is 70%.
This proposal requests 48 hours of VLBA "filler" time at X-band to reobserve with better sensitivity (detection limit 1.5-3 mJy) 127 sources not detected above 7-10 mJy.

fields.title: Mapping observations of chemically young compact cores
fields.abstract: According to a survey of the CCS and NH3 lines toward more than 100 dark cloud cores with the Nobeyama 45m radio telescope, we found possible candidates for chemically and physically very young cores. They show extremely high abundances of carbon-chain molecules relative to NH3. However, both carbon-chain and NH3 lines are systematically weaker than other cores. Our mapping observations revealed that some of the sources are as compact as the beam size of the NRO 45m telescope, 80". In addition, one of them has been identified as a weak dust continuum emission source. Therefore, it is likely that they are chemically very young with the extremely low NH3/CCS ratios, their H2 column densities are systematically lower than the typical cores, and they are compact. In order to study abundances and distributions of NH3 in these chemically young compact cores, we propose mapping observations of the NH3 lines with the GBT. Because sensitivities of previous observations were insufficient to detect weak NH3 lines, higher sensitivity with the GBT is essential. Our study will reveal the physical and chemical properties of dense cores close to the initial condition of dense core formation.

fields.title: A commensal method for the detection of fast transients using the VLBA - V-FASTR
fields.abstract: We propose to use the new capabilities of the DiFX software correlator installed at the SOC to continuously search all VLBA observations for fast radio transient signals, such as the single, powerful, highly dispersed burst discovered by Lorimer et al. (2007). This VLBA fast transient survey (V-FASTR) will be performed in a commensal mode with all VLBA observations, continuously searching filterbank data tapped off the DiFX correlator for short timescale bursts of radio emission that are highly dispersed after traveling large distances through the ionised intergalactic medium. The discovery of more examples of these rapid, highly dispersed transients can lead to a better understanding of the physical processes responsible for the bursts (i.e. merger of compact objects) and the ionisation history of the Universe.  This proposal is a renewal of BT111.  BT111 has used the fully implemented V-FASTR system, which has been collecting commensal data from the VLBA since July 2011.

fields.title: Mapping Two New Water Masers:  A Maser Disk Candidate and a Dwarf Merger
fields.abstract: We propose sequential  ELVA and VLBA mapping of two new single dish-detected water masers.  In two unrelated GBT programs, we have discovered a bright water maser in IIZw40, a dwarf galaxy merger, and a very strong water maser disk candidate in the nearby interacting spiral galaxy IC 750.  The EVLA maps will localize the masers for VLBA correlation. The ultimate goal of the VLBA mapping will be to determine the provenance of the maser emission, and if the geometry is a disk, to measure a black hole mass.  This work is part of a larger program to study the co-evolution of massive black holes and their galaxies in a range of contexts and growth and feedback settings.  We request 4 hours for the EVLA mapping and 24 hours for the VLBA.

fields.title: VLBA Search for Sub-Stellar Companion to the Unusual Ultracool Dwarf 2M1314+1320
fields.abstract: The radio emission from ultracool dwarfs opens a new horizon for the detection of sub-stellar companions through VLBI sub-milliarcsecond astrometry.  Since these objects already straddle the hydrogen burning limit, any detected companion will be sub-stellar.  The VLBI approach is particularly powerful in light of the limited feasibility of the traditional optical planet-detection techniques - radial velocity and transits - which are limited to early-M dwarfs.  We already conducted such an astrometric search for one ultracool dwarf and were able to significantly refine its parallax and proper motion (the search for residual reflex motion is on-going at the present).  Recently, we discovered the brightest radio emitting ultracool dwarf to date (2M1314+1320) and carried out an initial VLBI observation as a proof of concept.  The radio emission from this object has been stable for nearly a decade (it is detected in FIRST) and it therefore offers an excellent opportunity for an astrometric companion search.  Here we request 8 epochs of VLBA observations spread over a year and with a range of separations that will allow us to probe companions with orbits of ~1 week to ~6 months and with masses down to 2-10 Jupiter masses.

fields.title: Offset and Binary  Black Holes in Nearby Galaxies: Dual-Band Imaging
fields.abstract: Our large VLBA project BC 196 has been making a systematic X-band search for off-nuclear SMBHs and for tight SMBH pairs in a complete sample of 923 bright nearby 2MASS galaxies. Of the 492 compact sources detected, seven offset or binary black holes candidates were found. We request 24 hrs of VLBA time in order to perform high-fidelity, high-dynamic-range polarization imaging for all seven at C and X band. Observational parsec-scale results will be used to distinguish opaque compact cores from transparent extended jets via morphology, angular, spectral, and polarization characteristics. This will be compared with well known typical properties of blazar cores nearby single SMBH in order to confirm the candiates as probable offset or binary black holes.

fields.title: A Study of the Physics and Evolution of a Molecular Filament in Taurus
fields.abstract:
Recent observations by the Herschel Space Observatory have once again 
highlighted the importance of understanding the structure and evolution 
of filaments in star forming regions (e.g., Andr'e et al. 2010, Men'shchikov et al. 2010, 
Molinari et al. 2010, Arzoumanian et al. 2011).  
Mapping observations in dense molecular gas tracers are the next step
needed to trace the kinematic and turbulent 
structure of the filaments
and to study the complete 
life-cycle of dense cores within these filaments.
We propose to carry out fully sampled maps of NH3 and CCS in
the L1495/L1521 filament of Taurus with the KFPA 
to determine critical physical parameters
and to assess scenarios for filament formation.
Taurus is a great testbed for these studies because it is 
nearby and forming low-mass stars (no O and B stars) in a more isolated 
mode that is less spatially confusing than other nearby star forming 
regions.  We shall jointly analyze the proposed GBT observations 
with recent continuum (mid-infrared through submm), CO, and infrared polarization observations to study the relative importance of gravity (Jeans length), magnetic fields and turbulent dissipation along the L1495/L1521 filament.

fields.title: Imaging the SiO and H2O Masers Toward Three Symbiotic Stars
fields.abstract: We propose VLBA observations of the SiO and water maser emission associated with three symbiotic stars: V407 Cyg, V627 Cas, and R Aqr.  Symbiotic stars are binary systems consisting of a cool giant star transferring material to a hot white dwarf companion.  Although there are >200 symbiotic stars, only two were previously known to exhibit maser emission, R Aqr and H1-36.  Recently Cho & Kim (2010, ApJ, 719, 126) made single-dish detections of SiO and/or water maser emission from 19 new symbiotic stars.  They found the relative detection rates of v=1 vs. v=2 SiO masers to be different than those of isolated Mira variables and concluded that the presence of the hot companion was the cause of these observational differences.  We request 30 hours of VLBA time to image the various maser species toward three symbiotic stars.   These will represent the first such images for two of the stars:  V407 Cyg and V627 Cas, and for R Aqr the first image of the water masers.  For each star, we request phase referencing in order to register the relative locations of the SiO and water maser shells.   Results will be compared to those for isolated Mira variables.

fields.title: Testing the Jet Hypothesis in the Tidal Disruption Candidate Swift 1644+57
fields.abstract: We have demonstrated that the source Sw 1644+57 / GRB 110328A is best interpreted as a tidal disruption event of a star by a massive black hole in a galaxy at z=0.35 through a multi-wavelength campaign that spans radio to gamma-ray wavelengths. The strong and highly variable radio and X-ray light curves suggest that the source is actually a blazar, i.e., oriented close to the line of sight. VLBA observations have been crucial in making this case. We propose continued monitoring of this unique (once in three decades!) source with the VLBA in order to explore similarity of the radio source with ``standard'' Blandford-Konigl jets:  Can we detect expansion and/or outflow in the relativistic jet?  Does the jet precess?  Does the jet exhibit a core-shift?  Can we identify interaction of the jet with dense nuclear gas of the galaxy through polarimetry? This transient active galactic nucleus provides an unprecedented look at the coupled processes of accretion and jet formation comparable only to what we have seen in galactic microquasars.

fields.title: The Nuclear Environment of the First Radio Loud BALQSO J1556+3517
fields.abstract:
We propose second epoch VLBA observations of the Broad Absorption
Line Quasar J1556+3517, "the first radio
loud BALQSO", at 15 and 22 GHz. The primary goal would be to
fully resolve the flat spectrum radio core from the secondary
component for the first time (most likely at 22 GHz). Our previous
observations at 15 GHz partially resolved a secondary component at
PA ~ -35 degrees. Even though many BALQSOs are believed to
be viewed pole-on, based on high time variability brightness
temperatures, superluminal motion has never been detected in a
BALQSO. These second epoch observations are designed to look for
component motion relative to the first epoch. Furthermore, an
accurate determination of the radio jet direction, in consort with
the knowledge that the jet is viewed in a pole-on
orientation and the known PA of the optical continuum polarization
tightly restrict the quasar geometry. This will allow us to directly
constrain the relative orientations of the "dusty torus"
(scattering surface), accretion disk and the broad absorption line
outflow.

fields.title: Searching for dual radio cores in AGN with double-peaked optical emission lines
