fields.abstract: A sample of AGN displaying double-peaked emission line spectra has been defined by Wang et al. (2009).  Wang et al. (2009) suggest that the origin of the double-peaked profiles is due to dual black hole and accretion disk systems in these AGN, the result of galaxy merger activity in a lambda-CDM cosmology.  The best direct tracer of dual black hole systems in these AGN would be dual compact radio cores, as revealed by VLBI.  In project BT108 we observed the Wang et al. (2009) sample with the VLBA and found no dual compact cores.  However, based on detection statistics, we would expect of order only one binary black hole system from this sample size in an optimistic scenario (Tingay & Wayth 2011).  We seek VLBA time to extend our search for binary black holes via the study of a larger sample, based on the sample of double-peaked optical emission line AGN compiled by Smith et al. (2010).  This extended VLBA study will provide a far stronger statistical test of the Wang et al. (2009) hypothesis.

fields.title: Holographic imaging of the ionised ISM
fields.abstract: Making holographic images requires knowledge of the amplitude and phase of the electric field scattered by the objects being imaged. Using cyclic spectroscopy of radio pulsars it is now straightforward to determine the electric fields scattered by structures in the ionised ISM. But the information is returned in a form which is difficult to interpret, i.e. as a function of Doppler-shift and group delay. We have derived an integral transform method which converts delay-Doppler data to images of the free-electron density. This method will permit us to construct, for the first time, detailed pictures of the small-scale structure in the ionised ISM, thus revealing the nature of the puzzling ultra-high stress concentrations. Our method will also allow us to determine propagation delays on an absolute scale, thus providing a powerful technique for mitigating systematic errors in pulsar timing experiments. Here we propose to observe the binary pulsar J1518+4904 with the goal of constructing three-dimensional images of the ionised ISM on this line-of-sight.

fields.title: VLBA observations of the nearby binary AGN system Mrk739
fields.abstract: Binary AGN provide constraints on models of galaxy formation and a fundamental test of the merger-driven AGN scenario. So far, however, spatially resolved binary AGN are found in only a handful of galaxies. Recently, the discovery of a binary AGN in the galaxy Mrk739 using Chandra and Swift BAT data has been reported. The VLA radio images show emission from both cores but do not provide clear signature of AGN dual activity. Here, we propose two-frequencies VLBA observations of the radio emission from both nuclei in order to derive brightness temperature, morphological, and spectral index information of the emission to unveil the presence of components ascribable to AGN activity. The proposed project may provide a definite confirmation of the presence of a binary AGN in Mrk739 and relevant information on the AGN activity in this system, that is the second most nearby binary AGN discovered to date.

fields.title: Investigation of PSR J1719-1438 and its planetary mass companion
fields.abstract: PSR J1719-1438 is an intriguing binary pulsar recently discovered in the High Time Resolution Universe Survey for pulsars and fast transients. Its companion is of planetary mass (about the mass of Jupiter) but its low inferred density suggests that it may be an ultra-light carbon white dwarf. This system might hence descend from an ultra compact Low Mass X-ray Binary in which the companion nearly avoided destruction, representing hence a link between LMXB and solitary millisecond pulsars (MSPs), still a puzzle in the framework of the recycling scenario for MSP formation. With this proposal we aim at measuring the proper motion of this system and at assessing the potential for the GBT to measure its parallax in a reasonable time scale. These parameters are in fact fundamental to correctly determine the spin down rate of this pulsar wich, in turn, will allow us to study the pulsar parameters (spin down luminosity, surface magnetic field, spin down age, kinematics) resulting from the evolution of this as yet unique system. Detecting variations in the orbital period of the system caused by possible ablation of matter from the companion star, moreover, could help in contsraining its nature.

fields.title: Isotope Fractionation in Prestellar Cores: N-bearing Species
fields.abstract: The isotopic enrichments measured in volatile primitive materials probably had their origin in low-temperature (10K) chemistry similar to that found in molecular clouds. This has led to the proposal, supported by theory, that these anomalies derived their heritage from the prestellar period.  Recent models have shown that depletion of CO removes oxygen from the gas will promote significant 15N enhancements for N2 and ammonia (NH3) in CO-depleted, cold (7K) cores. We will conduct an observational study of NH3 and 15NH3 in prestellar cores L1521F, L1521E, and L1498 to investigate this theory. Multiple transitions will be observed for both species simultaneously in order to accurately obtain the isotope ratios and abundances. There have been limited studies conducted on isotopologues of various species in cores, primarily focused on high mass or warmer objects (Lis et al. 2010), while the theory is highly contingent on cold, dense objects and also suggests other N-bearing species may fractionate at different times.  Preliminary results from the ARO 12m have suggested extreme isotope fractionation in these objects from HCN and HNC.  We will observe NH3 isotopologues to gain a fundamental understanding of nitrogen fractionation for three prestellar cores to compare to models and observations of other species.

fields.title: The evolution of SN 2008iz in M82
fields.abstract: The recent discovery of supernova 2008iz in the nearby galaxy M82 offers the opportunity to observe this rare event in great detail. We propose to continue our monitoring of the evolution of the recently discovered supernova 2008iz in M82 with the VLBA, Effelsberg, and the GBT at frequencies from 1.6 to 8 GHz. The observations should be conducted every four months over the next year and will allow us to observe the expansion of the supernova shockwave into the interstellar medium.  Following the expansion of the ring together with EVLA monitoring will allow us to study many different phenomena, e.g. measure the expansion speed, the deceleration of the shock front, and the proper motion of the supernova shell relative to M81, get more information on the structure of the circumstellar medium, the evolution of the magnetic field, and the importance of radiative (and/or synchrotron self-absorption) losses. Furthermore, it will allow a detailed comparison with SN1993J, the other radio supernova traced in detail. Finally, a second intriguing radio transient in M82, which is in the field-of-view of the proposed observations, will be also monitored.

fields.title: The Megamaser Cosmology Project. V
fields.abstract: To constrain models of dark energy, a precise measurement of the Hubble constant provides the best complement to observations of the Cosmic Microwave Background. The Megamaser Cosmology Project (MCP) aims to determine Ho to +/- 3% by measuring geometric distances to water vapor megamasers in the Hubble flow. Based on observations of UGC 3789 and NGC 6264, the MCP has so far measured Ho = 67 +/- 6 km/s/Mpc, a precision comparable to the HST Key project measurement. We will improve this measurement by refining the distances to these two galaxies and incorporating results from additional galaxies. As a second important science result, the MCP is measuring the most precise (< 10%) masses of supermassive black holes in external galaxies by measuring the Keplerian rotation curves from these circumnuclear masers within a parsec of the black hole. These measurements are key to understanding the co-evolution of supermassive black holes and their host galaxies. In this proposal we request GBT, HSA, and EVLA time to map additional maser disks, improve the distance measurement to NGC 6264, measure distances to two recently discovered maser disks, and continue our successful survey for additional megamasers in narrow-line AGNs.

fields.title: Thermal OH Emission from Nearby Galaxies: A Feasibility Study
fields.abstract: The 18-cm thermal emission lines of the OH molecule remain poorly explored in the ISM of galaxies on the large scale. A recent paper has demonstrated for the first time the viability of detecting such emission in the general ISM of the Galaxy. Contrary to the well-observed 2.6-mm emission from the CO molecule, OH emission is very widespread in the Galaxy, with a distribution similar to that of HI both in space and in radial velocity. We propose to use the GBT for 24 hours in a feasibility study to detect thermal OH in M33 and to compare the observed profiles to the corresponding HI emission. This study will lay the foundation for more ambitious programs which could answer longstanding questions about the distribution of molecules and the degree to which the 21-cm line of HI is opaque in nearby galaxies.

fields.title: Timing new millisecond pulsars found in archival data
fields.abstract:
We request 19 hr of GBT time at 820 MHz over the course of a year to 
determine the basic spin, astrometric, binary, spectral and
polarimetric characteristics of newly discovered millisecond pulsars
from our re-analysis of archival Parkes multibeam data. One 4.8 ms
pulsar visible with the GBT has already been confirmed, along with two
others in the Southern sky which will be followed up at Parkes. The
time request here is to confirm our most promising remaining
candidates in the GBT sky, and time them. In addition to serving as
interesting objects in their own right, the millisecond pulsars we are
finding may be important additions to NANOGrav, and other pulsar
timing arrays aimed at detecting low-frequency gravitational waves.

fields.title: Molecular Survey towards Comet C/2009 P1 (Garradd)
fields.abstract: As part of a joint collaborative effort, a molecular survey of multiple volatile species is proposed to be conducted towards Comet C/2009 P1 (Garradd), a dynamically new comet. These observations will help constrain the origin of comets in the proto-solar disk, establish accurate abundances, determine the complex chemical network associated with these icy bodies, and compare variations between the two dynamic families. The projected magnitude of this object is ~5-6, brighter than most recent apparitions. Detailed studies of comets, especially new objects, are essential for their classification and further understanding of the distribution of molecular material throughout the Solar System.

fields.title: The Molecular Content of Optically "Invisible" z~2.6 HLIRGs
fields.abstract: We wish to use the GBT+Zpectrometer to complete a pilot program to measure 12CO(J=1-0) line emission from two prototypes of a population of heavily obscured z~2.6 HLIRGs unveiled by Spitzer in the NOAO Deep Wide-Field Survey region in Bootes. Their mid-IR spectra, rest-frame 1-10 um SEDS, and both bolometric and monochromatic 5 um luminosities show them to be powered by dust enshrouded AGN accreting near the Eddington limit, indicating a population of high-z "buried QSOs". These may represent a relatively short-lived AGN dominated phase in the evolution of sub-millimeter galaxies to massive ellipticals and bulges. The Zpectrometer data will yield molecular and dynamical information, allowing us to take the first steps in relating these objects to other high-z galaxy populations. Precise CO redshifts and line fluxes will also greatly facilitate follow-up work. At the targets' redshifts the 115 GHz line shifts to the Ka-band. The Zpectrometer's bandwidth, sensitivity, and observing efficiency are essential for this project. This proposal was approved last year, however, only minimal time was scheduled. We are therefore resubmitting.

fields.title: Radar Speckle Observations of Asteroids During 2012
fields.abstract:
Near-Earth asteroids are a diverse population of objects having orbits that either cross or come near that of the Earth.  Currently over 8000 are known; the number is increasing at about 1000 per year. Asteroids' trajectories are coupled to their pole directions. Despite this, pole directions have been measured for only about 30 near-Earth asteroids.


We have developed radar speckle tracking to determine asteroid pole directions, transmitting from Arecibo or Goldstone and receiving with the VLBA.  The reflected radio waves from each point on a radar target's surface interfere with each other, producing a radar speckle pattern.  As the target rotates, the speckles move in the same direction as the surface.  Tracking the speckle motion between stations allows us to determine the target's spin state. 


We have used radar speckle tracking with the VLBA to study asteroids for the last three years, and would like to continue this program.  We request a total of 14 hours of time for speckle tracking observations of the near-Earth asteroids 2011 CP4, 2010 KK37, and Toutatis, and new discoveries that are also strong radar targets.

fields.title: Imaging a Nova Blastwave
fields.abstract:
Recent observations have shown that the initial phase of the nova blastwave is poorly understood.  There are several indications that the simple Hubble flow model does not fit nova in this early time, namely that the circum-binary environment does not have a simple 1/r^2 profile.  The best way to determine what is going on is to image the blastwave.  We propose to observe every nova outburst within 1-3 days and approximately one week of detection with the VLBA.  With this we hope to 1) detect 10^6 K gas proving the development of shocks early in the nova; 2) look for asymmetries in the ejecta which will reveal asymmetry of the initial blastwave; 3) follow the evolution between in the first days of explosion;
4) obtain a precise initial position for the nova which, among other things will help with later interpretation.  We ask for 4 hours per new nova at 2Gbps split into two observations.

The Megamaser Cosmology Project (MCP) aims to determine Ho to +/- 3% by measuring geometric distances to water vapor megamasers in the Hubble flow. fields.title: Improvement of calibrator positions used for pulsar astrometry
fields.abstract:
We propose to observe 68 compact extragalactic sources selected 
as calibrators for pulsar parallax determination and improve their 
absolute positions to a level of 0.1 mas. As a result, it will 
become possible to derive absolute positions of pulsars to that 
level of accuracy. Combining pulsar positions from VLBI with
pulsar positions from timing we will be able 1) to determine 
orientation of the dynamic coordinate system with respect 
to the kinematic coordinate with accuracy 0.1 mas;
2) to evaluate systematic errors of kinematic and dynamic
coordinate system at the nanoradian level of accuracy.

fields.title: 100 muas absolute astrometry of southern quasars for connection with Gaia
fields.abstract:
We propose to observe 50 optically bright quasars in the zone
[-40, 0] degrees as a pilot study and determine 1) their positions 
with accuracy 0.1 mas and 2) their core-shifts. Positions of these sources 
will be determined with Gaia with a similar accuracy. The overall goal
of the proposal is to make possible to make comparison of radio and 
optical coordinate systems, to investigate their rotation, zonal errors, 
and the non-alignment of the radio and optical positions caused by 
both radio and optical structures. This study is critically important 
for validation of both techniques. This proposal is complimentary
to proposals GC030, GC034 that targeted the northern hemisphere.

fields.title: A scintillation-based search for Galactic Center pulsars
fields.abstract: The discovery and subsequent timing of a pulsar experiencing the strong gravitational field close to the black hole at the center of the Galaxy would yield an unprecedented test of General Relativity.  Whilst such a pulsar has been sought for decades, the hyper-strong scattering in the Galactic Center environment has thwarted any discoveries to date.  This proposal makes use of a novel approach - the identification of a Galactic Center pulsar through its scintillating emission, rather than through its pulsations.  The sensitivity of this search using the GBT at 8 GHz will be comparable to or better than past efforts, and crucially it is sensitive to millisecond pulsars (MSPs).  MSPs offer the best potential for extremely precise tests of General Relativity, and have been selected against in past Galactic Center pulsar surveys due to their short pulse periods.

fields.title: Proper motion of the "core" of the quasar 3C 345 and the stability of the ICRF
fields.abstract: The international Celestial Reference Frame (ICRF) is the most fundamental of all reference frames. It is defined by compact extragalactic radio sources distributed across the sky. Their VLBI-determined coordinates and proper motions have <1 milliarcsecond and <1 milliarcsecond/year accuracies, respectively. Higher accuracies are needed for astrophysical studies of emission close to the supermassive black holes of quasars, fundamental astrometry, tie of other reference frames to the ICRF, spacecraft navigation, cosmology, and tests of general relativity. The most accurate proper motion measurements are possible via VLBI phase-reference observations of compact radio sources nearby on the sky. The quasar 3C 345 has been observed by us in this way from 1980 onward and provides a unique example of probing the proper motion, or lack thereof, of a quasar. We propose to add one more set of observations to our previous ones from the 1980's and from 2004 to confirm our intriguing proper motion measurement of the core of 11.8+-2.3 microarcseconds/year, the first ever, improve our accuracy, study the opacity effect near the core, and contribute to our understanding of the dynamics of the "core" of a quasar and to the stability of the ICRF.

fields.title: A Complete W Band Survey toward the Galactic Center Region Sgr B2(N-LMH)
fields.abstract: In 2007, the Prebiotic Molecule Survey (PRIMOS) was undertaken to provide complete spectral line data between 300 MHz and 50 GHz toward the preeminent source of molecules in the Galaxy,  Sgr B2(N-LMH). Sgr B2 (N-LMH) is the preeminent source for studies of large complex interstellar molecules and as such, numerous molecular line surveys have been conducted from the mm to submm range. However, the last spectral line survey of this source in the 4mm regime was in 1989 by Barry Turner where average spectral rms values of ~80mK were achieved with a beam size of over 1 arcmin. With the new W-band receiver on the GBT, we will be able to achieve rms noise levels of ~7mK with a beam size of ~9" on average allowing for more complete searches of weak molecular features. A thorough, sensitive survey at 4mm wavelengths, combined with the already existent GBT PRIMOS data will provide scientist a more complete picture of the chemical composition, physical properties (temperature, density) and kinematics of this complex source allowing a more absolute understanding of interstellar clouds in our molecular origins.

fields.title: Baryon Acoustic Oscillations with 21cm Intensity Mapping
fields.abstract: We propose a multi-year program to make precise measurements of the large scale structure of the universe using recently-developed 21cm intensity mapping techniques. The program will create spectral maps of 500 deg2, spanning the frequency range 700 to 900 MHz (.58 < z < 1). The resulting high-sensitivity measurement of the spatial distribution of neutral hydrogen will allow study of the evolution of neutral hydrogen over cosmic time. We will detect and measure the baryon acoustic oscillation feature allowing a test of dark energy models. The survey requires 3000 hours of integration time on the Green Bank Telescope, using a new 2 x 2 feed horn array, which we will provide. The survey will make use of periods of low demand. The construction of the multi-pixel receiver will require up to 12 months. During that period, we request a 100 hour/semester allocation of time to continue our ongoing path-finding program. We need this data flow to continue development of algorithms for radio frequency interference mitigation, cross-linked mapping, and foreground subtraction. All of these techniques will be essential to this program and also to the proposed Hydrogen Epoch of Reionization Arrays (HERA) program of 21cm cosmology.

fields.title: GBT 68--92 GHz Spectral Line Survey of Orion-KL
fields.abstract: We propose to carry out a spectral line survey of Orion-KL with the new 4mm Receiver on the GBT.   The observations will probe deeper than previous surveys and will observed at low frequencies which have not yet been previously explored.  The observations are better matched to the size of the Orion-KL bright core than the previous Turner NRAO 11m survey, and this modest survey will improve upon the sensitivity of the 11m survey by a factor of 100.   The results of the full survey will be made public immediately for use by other teams.

fields.title: Cool Gas Physics in Brightest Cluster Galaxies.
fields.abstract: The cooling and reheating of dense gas in rich galaxy clusters is a process essential to high-z galaxy formation as well as low-z ''cooling flows'', but it is not yet understood. We propose to test two competing models on the basis of their predictions of the pressures in the molecular gas phase. We will observe the CO bright cD galaxies in Abell 1068 and MKW 4s in the J=1-0 HCN and HCO+ lines, whose density dependencies are diagnostic in the expected range.

fields.title: Confronting accretion disc and jet theory with astrometry and imaging of SS Cyg
fields.abstract: The disc instability model (DIM) is the prevailing model that not only explains the basic properties of the outbursts of dwarf novae, a subclass of cataclysmic variables, but also forms the basis for understanding outbursts of X-ray binaries.  However, at the HST-derived parallax distance, the outbursts of the prototypical dwarf nova, SS Cyg, are too bright to be explained by this model, placing our whole theoretical understanding of these classes of sources in doubt.  The astrometric parameters derived during recent VLBA observations of an outburst of SS Cyg were inconsistent with the HST-derived parallax and proper motion of the source. Since a revision of the distance is clearly necessary, we propose further VLBA observations of SS Cyg, taken during two different outbursts over the next year, for a total allocation of 16h.  This will provide the definitive distance to the source, hence testing whether the DIM is applicable to SS Cyg. Moreover, the existing VLBA observations showed the first tentative detection of resolved jets from a dwarf nova. Given the marginal significance of this key result, the increased bandwidth now available at the VLBA will provide a more sensitive test for the existence of these resolved jets.

fields.title: OH observations of comets at extreme heliocentric distances
fields.abstract: We propose to make OH mapping observations of four comets:  C/2009 P1 Garradd, 96P/Machholz, C/2011 F1 LINEAR, and C/2011 L4 PANSTARRS, in order to constrain gas outflow velocities and production rates for these unusual comets.  First, we would continue to monitor C/2009 P1 Garradd, the first comet we have detected with GBT outside 2 AU heliocentric distance, and thus an unprecedented opportunity to follow the evolution of a single comet with this technique for an extended period of time.  Second, the observations of 96P/Machholz represent a first opportunity to observe a comet inside 0.4 AU heliocentric distance, a region in which gas velocities for comets are very poorly characterized.  Finally, the long period comets C/2011 F1 LINEAR and C/2011 L4 PANSTARRS can be observed outside 3 AU heliocentric distance, more than twice the distance probed to date in this study.  The proposed observations will also contribute to our monitoring program of OH in comets.

fields.title: H2O maser in the narrow-line Seyfert 1 galaxy NGC 4051
fields.abstract:
The narrow-line Seyfert 1 (NLS1) galaxy is a peculiar class of active galaxy hosting a smaller-mass black hole with higher mass accretion rates onto it, according to hard-Xray measurements.
Extragalactic 22 GHz H2O masers allow the angular structure of active galactic nuclei (AGN) to be probed. 22 GHz H2O maser  in the NLS1 galaxy NGC4051 was first discovered by Hagiwara et al. (2003). The maser remains unresolved at 70 milliarcsecond (3.5 pc), with earlier VLA-A observations. The angular structure of an accretion disk in this NLS1 galaxy at radii << 1 pc should be explored at milliarcsecond angular resolution enabled by VLBI in order to check if the disk inclination or thickness is different from those of Type2 Seyferts. This is very important to address the AGN "Unified Theory". Sensitive VLBA+GBT observations for measuring the distribution of a number of velocity components straddling  the galaxy's systemic velocity quasi-symmetrically will be able to resolve the accretion disk in a Type 1 Seyfert nucleus for the first time on scales of sub-parsec.

fields.title: Continuing the GBT All-Sky 350-MHz Pulsar Survey
fields.abstract: We propose to continue the all-sky 350-MHz pulsar survey begun as the GBNCC (Green Bank North Celestial Cap) survey in 2009.  In this "Stage II" of the survey we will push to lower declinations yet avoid the Arecibo declination range and the Galactic plane as much as possible. The primary science goal is to discover new millisecond pulsars (MSPs) needed by the NANOGrav project for the direct detection of the nanohertz stochastic gravitational wave background. Two sets of independent simulations suggest that we will find 10 to dozens of new MSPs, and >200 "normal" pulsars in this proposed survey area, which covers ~25% of the GBT sky.  With 2-min pointings and 75% observing efficiency, we request ~1500 hrs (over 3 years) for this stage of the survey.  The large gain of the GBT along with the high time and frequency resolution of GUPPI will make this survey more sensitive by factors of ~5 for slow pulsars and 10-20 for MSPs than the Jodrell 70cm survey of the Northern sky. In addition, the amazingly RFI-free band near 350MHz will provide a unique legacy dataset for the astronomical community.

fields.title: Unveiling the nature of galactic bubbles: search for OH masers
fields.abstract: About 400 compact shells have been discovered with SPITZER in the MIPSGAL 24 $\mu$m survey of the galactic plane. The majority of these "bubbles" do not have any counterpart at shorter wavelengths; only about 10\% of them has an identification, being most PNe. The general suspect is that they are circumstellar envelopes of evolved stars, from SNRs to LBV, PNe, post-AGB and AGB. The goal of this proposal is to search, among the non identified bubbles with no radio counterpart, for OH maser. The presence of any on the three lines at 1612 and/or at 1665/1667 MHz could indicate an AGB or post-AGB star and, considering that each maser line appears at particular stages, we could also attribute the evolutive phases. The presence of the 1720 MHz maser line can indicate the interaction of SNR ejecta with molecular clouds. The detection of any of the four OH maser line is of great importance to classify the galactic "bubbles".

fields.title: Expansion of the NANOGrav pulsar timing array project
fields.abstract: Direct detection of gravitational waves (GW) is a major goal in experimental physics and will revolutionize astrophysics, opening an entirely new spectrum for exploration.  Precision pulsar timing stands an excellent chance of being the first method to accomplish this feat.  Combining data from many objects into a pulsar timing array (PTA) makes GW detection possible.  Increasing the number of pulsars in the array improves sensitivity -- the detection significance improves approximately linearly with the number of pulsars. Observing more pulsars also helps mitigate intrinsic systematic timing effects. The past year has seen a unexpected and unprecedented number of new millisecond pulsars (MSPs) discovered, due to several ongoing radio sky surveys (GBT 350-MHz surveys; PALFA) and targeted radio searches of Fermi-identified gamma-ray point sources.  Here we propose an expansion of our ongoing PTA project to take advantage of these new sources.

fields.title: Confirmation of Intermittent Radio Pulsars in the Sculptor Dwarf Galaxy
fields.abstract: We have conducted a search for pulsars in the direction of the Sculptor Spheroidal Dwarf Galaxy (SSdG) using the Green Bank Radio telescope. This search has resulted in the detection of two excellent detections that appear as sporadic radio bursts in our single pulse searches. These sources are good candidates of intermittent radio pulsars such as the Rotating Radio Transients (RRATs).  Building on this recent detection we propose here to perform follow up observations of the SSdG to confirm their astrophysical nature and constrain better their fluxes, burst rate and periods if possible. Confirming these sources in the SSdG would imply that neutron stars can be formed in this kind of stellar environments dominated by a population of old stars.

fields.title: Bistatic Radar Imaging of Near-Earth Asteroids
fields.abstract:
Radar observations are an extremely powerful technique for studying near-Earth asteroids (NEAs) and can provide delay-Doppler images with a range resolution as fine as 7.5 m/pixel. Such data quality can be exceeded only by a spacecraft rendezvous or flyby. Radar observations have shown that the near-Earth asteroids are a very diverse population in which we continue to discover unusual objects. 


The resolution of radar images in time delay is determined by the transmitter coding. Currently, we can code Arecibo's transmission to provide 7.5 m range resolution. The resolution in Doppler frequency is set by the length of the Fourier transform used to process the data.  Bistatic observations, transmitting from Arecibo and receiving with the GBT, allow us to use much longer transforms, providing much higher frequency resolution.


During the first half of 2012, Arecibo will observe roughly one near-Earth asteroid per week. For perhaps 20% of the targets, bistatic imaging will be very useful.  We request 15 hours of triggered transient time, to be used during the first half of 2012 for bistatic imaging of such targets.

fields.title: A Pulsar Companion to PSR B1828-11?
fields.abstract: PSR B1828-11 is well known for its characteristic periodic variations in spin-down rate and profile shape. This has variously been explained as free precession (Stairs et al. 2000) or mode-switching between discrete magnetospheric/spin-down states (Lyne et al. 2010), with possible implications for timing noise in all pulsars. In Rosen et al. (2011), we proposed that a non-radial oscillation model may be able to explain these quasi-periodic fluctuations. Currently, we are using the Green Bank Telescope (GBT) to test our theory by fitting our model to single-pulse data from PSR B1828-11 during its different spin-down rate states. Our first GBT observation of PSR B1828-11 revealed a previously unknown pulsar in the same 820 MHz beam, with nearly the same dispersion measure and almost exactly twice the spin period. Subsequent 2 GHz observations revealed that these two pulsars are several parsecs apart, but the high coincidence of the spin periods and dispersion measures raises the question of whether the two pulsars were once physically related. As our current proposal expires, we request GBT observations to start timing this new pulsar and to continue our long-term observations of PSR B1828-11.

fields.title: Venus spin dynamics
fields.abstract:
We request 12 hours of antenna time to obtain 8 instantaneous spin
rate measurements of Venus using the Goldstone Solar System Radar
(GSSR) and the Green Bank Telescope (GBT) at X-band.  Our observations
provide the only practical monitoring of Venus length-of-day
variations.  They reveal variations in the spin rate due to the
exchange of angular momentum between the atmosphere and the solid
planet.  Our long-term goal is to quantify daily, seasonal, and
secular changes, enabling important investigations of the climate and
atmospheric dynamics on Venus, including its super-rotation.  We also
seek to measure the spin axis orientation to 5'' to quantify the
current obliquity state, which is poorly understood.  An additional
long-term goal is the measurement of the polar moment of inertia of
the planet, an unmeasured yet fundamental constraint on interior
models.  We will also obtain measurements of the spin of Mercury
during the same time allocation to contribute to our-long term
monitoring of the spin state of Mercury.

fields.title: A Pulsar Companion to PSR B1828-11?
fields.abstract: PSR B1828-11 is well known for its characteristic periodic variations in spin-down rate and profile shape. This has variously been explained as free precession (Stairs et al. 2000) or mode-switching between discrete magnetospheric/spin-down states (Lyne et al. 2010), with possible implications for timing noise in all pulsars. In Rosen et al. (2011), we proposed that a non-radial oscillation model may be able to explain these quasi-periodic fluctuations. Currently, we are using the Green Bank Telescope (GBT) to test our theory by fitting our model to single-pulse data from PSR B1828-11 during its different spin-down rate states. Our first GBT observation of PSR B1828-11 revealed a previously unknown pulsar with nearly the same dispersion measure and almost exactly twice the spin period. Subsequent observations revealed that these two pulsars are several parsecs apart, but the high coincidence of the spin periods and dispersion measures raises the question of whether the two pulsars were once physically related, a question possibly resolved with proper motion measurements. We request VLBA measurements to obtain the accurate position and proper motion measurements necessary to plausibly confirm or deny an association between the two pulsars.

fields.title: CS(1-0) Survey of Local (U)LIRGs
fields.abstract: Similar to HCN and HCO+, CS traces molecular gas at slightly higher density ($\ge 10^5$~cm$^{-3}$). Dense gas is a better indicator of star formation rate and starburst activity than total molecular gas (traced by CO), as demonstrated by tight HCN--IR correlation from Galactic dense cores to extreme starbursts/QSOs at high-z. CS is likely to be better tracer of dense gas than HCN/HCO+ since CS is a stable molecule and abundantly observed in Galactic star-forming regions. We propose here a GBT CS(1-0) survey of local (U)LIRGs to statistically study the spectral line energy distribution (SLED), total dense gas content and excitation (high-J CS observations we have obtained so far won't probe relatively cool and tenuous dense molecular gas). We request 22.5 hours to observe 14 (U)LIRGs (15 pointings) for this season. The survey also serves as a pathfinder for high resolution imaging of dense gas in local (U)LIRGs with the EVLA and provides fully studied SLEDs of local analogs to high-z ULIRGs, to be probed by ALMA.

fields.title: Timing Followups of New RRAT Discoveries in GBT 350MHz Drift Scan
fields.abstract: We have recently discovered new RRAT candidates in data obtained in the 2007 GBT350 Drift Scan survey. These sources need to be further studied in order to measure the fundamental parameter Pdot (spin down rate) for each RRAT, allowing to place these objects in the P/Pdot neutron star phase space and learn more about the origin of RRAT emission. Furthermore, determining these sources' physical properties as a population is crucial in order to compare with properties of conventional radio pulsars. We request GBT observations to confirm these sources and perform follow-up timing observations for each source.

fields.title: Spin state and interior of Mercury
fields.abstract: We request 4.5 hours of time in trimester 12A to measure the spin state of Mercury with the radar speckle displacement effect, combining the Goldstone Solar System Radar and the Green Bank Telescope at X-band.  The additional data will sample the spin state near aphelion, a region that is currently very poorly sampled in our data set.  The new measurements are needed to refine the determination of the obliquity and the amplitude of the forced librations, to characterize the long-period libration component (period of ~12 years), and to characterize deviations of the pole from the strict Cassini state.  The precision of the ground-based estimates will ultimately dictate the precision of the core size measurement, and therefore the quality of inferences regarding the interior structure, thermal evolution, and magnetic field generation of this end-member terrestrial planet.  The GBT observations are critical for the interpretation of MESSENGER mission data.

fields.title: Mapping the Low Column Density HI Around M31
fields.abstract: We propose to map a region of diffuse, low column density HI near M31. This gas was discovered by the WSRT wide-field HI survey along with a diffuse HI stream between M31 and M33 (being mapped as part of GBT11B-051).  HI observations of M33, stellar observations of M33 and M31, and numerical modeling suggest that this may be a tidal feature due to a past interaction between M33 and M31, and is thus an analog of the main body and Leading Arm of the Magellanic Stream. The area of our map will total 12 square degrees. Information on the kinematics of the HI gas will help further our understanding of the physical processes involved with the interaction of the M31 with this gas and, by analogy, the Leading Arm(s) as well probe the intergalactic medium and the halo of M31. We will also use our observations in conjunction with a least-action based method to fit for the dynamics of this gas and orbital history of the M31-M33 system. The GBT is the only instrument capable of mapping this very faint emission at high resolution for the foreseeable future.

fields.title: Polar-aligned Radio Structures in Active Late-type Binaries
fields.abstract: Recent high-precision astrometric VLBI observations of several active late-type binaries has allowed registration of the radio images on the binary orbit with an uncertainty smaller than a stellar radius. These observations reveal that the radio emission often is associated with co-rotating coronal loop structures whose footprints are aligned with the poles. Both x-ray data and optical observations of persistent polar spots  support this hypothesis but the sample size is presently too small (2 objects) to determine whether this is a common property of active close binaries. We propose testing the polar model by multi-epoch HSA observations of two additional nearby active close binaries. Both systems are relatively nearby, radio-loud,  and well-studies at other bands, making them excellent targets to test the polar model.

fields.title: Directly confirming the existence of jets in quiescent X-ray binaries
fields.abstract: We request four 8-hour epochs of dynamically-scheduled VLBA time to verify our preliminary evidence for a preferred axis in the black hole X-ray binary system V404 Cygni.  After subtracting off the known proper motion and parallax signatures, the astrometric residuals are aligned with the known magnetic field direction in this system, suggesting that the radio emission arises from a partially self-absorbed compact jet.  Verifying this result would prove beyond doubt the existence of jets in quiescent black hole systems, ruling out emission from a corona or thermal disc wind that have previously been suggested for radio-quiet quasars.  Such a detection would also allow us to measure the size scale of the quiescent jets for the first time, determining how the size scale of the jets varies with the radio emission, often used as a proxy for jet power.

fields.title: Timing followups of GBNCC pulsars
fields.abstract: We are requesting time to perform long term timing observations of radio pulsars discovered in the Green Bank North Celestial Cap(GBNCC, GBT09C-057) pulsar survey. In the past six months, ten new pulsars have been discovered including one millisecond pulsar, two recycled pulsars, and seven other pulsars. The followup observations of these new sources, which are not observable by the Arecibo Observatory, will help us to determine the physical properties such as spin, astrometric, and (if applicable) binary parameters of these newly discovered objects. Such parameters provide information about neutron star populations and classifications. The millisecond pulsar will likely be useful in the efforts to detect gravitational waves using a pulsar timing array.

fields.title: Constraining black hole formation with triggered VLBA astrometry
fields.abstract: We propose to extend our pilot program to measure proper motions of black hole X-ray binaries using triggered VLBA observations during the hard spectral state phases of their outbursts. Combined with radial velocities this will yield their velocities in the Galaxy, carrying unique information about the formation of the black hole.  Since a previous VLA survey determined that quiescent black holes are too faint for astrometric VLBI observations, black hole astrometry must be carried out via triggered observations during a hard X-ray spectral state at the beginning and end of an outburst.  We propose 3 VLBA observations per outburst, for 2 outbursts, to accurately constrain the proper motion of 2 black hole X-ray binaries, to demonstrate of the feasibility of this approach.  If successful, then by extending this program to create a sufficient sample of triggered astrometric observations to provide a full, unbiased survey of proper motions, we will eventually be able to determine which black holes formed in direct collapse, which in a supernova and for these put constraints on the asymmetric kicks they received. In turn these answers will provide important input for the theoretical understanding of the formation of black holes from massive stars.

fields.title: Probing jet acceleration and collimation in stellar-mass black holes
fields.abstract: We propose intensive radio monitoring of an outburst of a Galactic black hole X-ray binary with the VLBA and EVLA to both improve our understanding of jet formation and acceleration in these systems, and to provide insights into the formation of jets in accreting systems of all kinds. The first observation, taken in the hard X-ray spectral state prior to the main flare, will be used to determine the location of the compact core jet. The following seven observations, taken during the transition to the soft state, will resolve the morphological changes in the jet during the transition. Three further observations over the following two weeks will measure the proper motions of the relativistically-moving ejecta and determine whether the jets are decelerating. By extrapolating back to zero-separation from the core location, we will ascertain the exact moment of ejection. Comparing this with X-ray spectral and timing signatures prior to, and following, the ejection will determine the causal sequence of events in the inner accretion flow that leads to the production of relativistic jets. Three final observations taken during the reverse transition back to the hard state will resolve the re-ignition of the compact jets.

fields.title: Observations of BGPS sources in the l=30 field
fields.abstract: We are proposing to observe 142 of the 806 BGPS sources in the l=30 field of the Galactic Plane in the NH_3 (1,1) and (2,2) inversion transitions. We have associated 664 BGPS sources with GRS clouds, with the remaining sources having ambiguous associations. In those particular lines of sight, there are small, low-velocity dispersion clouds which fell below the detection threshold of the GRS cloud catalogue as well as clouds in the catalogue. Current associations of these 142 sources have them associated with these small, weak GRS sources which are less robust than the associations with the larger clouds. These observations will confirm these associations and will also allow us to test whether these sources are part of a separate population. These associations will allow us to then measure the clump-to-cloud mass ratio with relation to the Galactic structure that is found in the l=30 field.

fields.title: Characterizing the mJy compact radio source population
fields.abstract: We propose to use the VLBA to survey a large number of sources from the VLA FIRST radio catalog, to provide unambiguous active galactic nuclei (AGN) identifications and source counts in the flux density range of 1 mJy to 100 mJy. Our project will fill a gap between historical all-sky VLBI calibrator surveys for the brightest compact sources and recent deep VLBI surveys which target sub-mJy sources over areas of order 1 square degree. In doing so, we will unambiguously identify large numbers of AGN, something which is difficult using other means, and study their evolution in the local (z<1) universe. As a result we will construct the differential VLBI source counts and deliver, where available, optical identifications from SDSS data. Our project is designed to be carried out in short blocks, with a low minimum number of antennas, and can be used to fill small gaps in the VLBA schedule.

fields.title: Molecular Gas Excitation in Lensed, Herschel-Selected Submillimeter Galaxies
fields.abstract: Herschel has discovered a population of extremely rare, bright, gravitationally lensed submillimeter galaxies (SMGs)-- strongly magnified versions of the most intense starbursts throughout cosmic time. The magnification is fortunate, as it enables detailed studies of individual systems and large samples in only moderate amounts of observing time, making SMG studies feasible with single-dish telescopes. We propose to use the GBT/Zpectrometer to observe CO(1-0) emission toward a sample of 16 SMGs from HerMES detected in (most likely) CO(3-2) emission with CARMA (and to search for blind CO redshifts in two more). This will allow us to study CO excitation in these intriguing systems, and to investigate the possible impact of differential lensing on CO line intensity and line width ratios (prime diagnostics for the physical properties of the cold and star-forming gas). It will also allow us to determine total molecular gas masses and gas-to-dust ratios, and to constrain the spatially integrated star formation law. This comprehensive program will have a major impact on studies of star formation in the early universe, and will give the GBT a key role in maximizing the legacy value of the largest area Herschel surveys.

fields.title: NH3 mapping observations along the major axes of nearby galaxies
fields.abstract: We propose to use the GBT 100-m telescope to map ammonia along the major axes of three nearby spiral galaxies -- IC 342, NGC 3627, and M 51, with the multi-beam receiver KFPA. Star formation has been proofed to be directly related to dense molecular gas. The physical conditions of the dense gas, as density, temperature and pressure, are important to understand star formation in galaxies. But up to now, most of dense gas studies concentrate in the nuclear regions of galaxies, while the dense gas on the arms and disks is still poorly studied, even for the nearest galaxies .  We aim to observe ammonia (1,1) to (4,4) inversion lines simultaneously,  as probers of dense gas properties, to determine the physical properties of the molecular gas and distinguish the difference environment of star formation on the spiral arms and in the nuclear regions. In total 20 hours are requested.

fields.title: Simultaneous wide-band and spectral-line imaging of the Galactic plane
fields.abstract: We propose to use the GBT to provide short-spacing measurements for the approved EVLA project VLA/11B-157. The objective of the project is to make wideband mosaicked images of the CTB-80 region in L-band (1-2 GHz), at high spectral resolution, to demonstrate the GBT+EVLA's potential for widefield spectral surveys. These observations will provide extremely sensitive continuum images, together with detailed maps of the spectral index and polarization and three-dimensional models of the rotation screens along the line-of-sight.  In addition, the project will obtain high-resolution, high-sensitivity, unbiased surveys of the HI 21cm line, all four OH transitions and radio recombination lines (both H and C), all with about 1 km/s resolution over at least 500 km/s. Many sources we are interested have angular scales larger than that can be measured with the EVLA. Moreover, as shown by Rau & Cornwell (2011), it is essential to have short-spacing information of the same field to unambiguously reconstruct both spatial and spectral structure of sources with all scales at the aimed sensitivity level and at the angular resolution allowed by the highest spacial frequency sampled by the ELVA.

fields.title: The RMS Survey: Massive Star Formation throughout the Galaxy
fields.abstract: We propose to map the ammonia (1,1) and (2,2) emission towards a well-selected sample of embedded massive young stars using the GBT. These data will be used to derive the physical conditions of the molecular clumps associated with the formation of the most massive stars, such as the optical depth, column density, temperature (rotation and kinetic), masses (viral and local thermal equilibrium (LTE)) and physical sizes, as well as revealing details of their velocity structure. As well as providing a wealth of information on the internal structure, mass and size of individual clumps these observations will allow variations in these parameters to be investigated throughout the Galaxy. With these quantities in hand we will investigate how the star formation efficiency and metallicity change as a function of galactocentric radius and whether there is significant variations between clumps located within the spiral arms and those located in the inner-arm regions, or between the different spiral arms themselves. These observations will facilitate higher resolution follow-up observations with the EVLA by providing the necessary "zero" spacing information.

fields.title: The Radio Ammonia Mid-Plane Survey
fields.abstract: We propose the Radio Ammonia Mid-Plane Survey (RAMPS) which will map the Galactic plane in NH3 and H20 using the K-band Focal Plane Array on the GBT. RAMPS has three main goals: (1) to study the evolution of physical conditions in the dense gas forming high-mass protostars, (2) to use the dynamic state of filaments to understand both filament and cluster formation, (3) to use H2O masers to understand the galactic distribution of star formation. The NH3 maps will isolate the dense star-forming gas and measure the temperatures, column densities, velocities (for kinematic distances), and dynamical state of this dense gas. H2O masers will pinpoint the presence of both low- and high-mass protostars. RAMPS will blindly map between 10<l<40 degrees and -1<b<+1 degrees in under 1400 hours; as a blind survey it will avoid the selection effects of a targeted survey and yet (due to efficiency gains) be as fast as a targeted survey. The RAMPS team combines the expertise of KFPA array users with scientists known for leading large Galactic plane surveys. The RAMPS archive will be a legacy for all astronomers.

fields.title: HCN and HCO+ mapping in the galaxy NGC 4303
fields.abstract: We propose to use the new 4mm receiver to map the dense gas distribution and study the star formation activity in the nearby barred spiral galaxy NGC 4303. This galaxy offers a wide range of star formation activity in a number of dynamically distinct environments in a small area (an AGN, a bar, bar ends, an inner ring and spiral structure). The star formation surface density varies by over three orders of magnitude and while there are regions with strong CO emission and high star formation activity there are also areas with strong CO emission and no star formation! One possibility for the lack of star formation is that these regions are made of two phases -- a dense, star forming phase and a diffuse phase, created by cloud shearing due to the bar tidal forces, which dominates the CO emission and kinematics. Here we propose to investigate the dense molecular gas fraction by mapping the inner disk of NGC 4303 in the dense gas tracers HCN and HCO+, and comparing these data to CO (1-0) emission and star formation activity at a matched resolution of 10 arcseconds.

fields.title: A short study of bright Solar Sytem objects using the CCB
fields.abstract: We propose to observe Europa, Callisto, Ganymede, Vesta, and Ceres using the Caltech Continuum Backend in order to follow up some interesting results we have obtained with the same instrument observing Iapetus.  Our Iapetus observations showed a relatively narrow feature with a brightness temperature of only 20K.  Previous radio observations of solar system objects tend to be spaced at intervals of a factor of two in wavelength.  The CCB on the other hand completely covers nearly a factor of 1.5 in wavelength but with spacing of only 0.1 wavelengths.  This unique spacing allows us to probe astrophysical phenomena such as reststralen bands and some compositional features that are averaged or skipped over in previous submm-cm observations.  Thus we would like to explore several additional solar system objects in this same manner in order to provide context to our intriguing Iapetus results.

fields.title: The HC3N* systematic trends in the kinematics of massive star forming regions
fields.abstract: Hot cores (HCs) are deeply embedded, dense (n > 10^7cm-3), hot (T > 200 K), and chemically rich condensations, which are considered to be the earliest stages of massive star formation. Based on observations of rotational transitions from different excited levels (HC3N*) toward HCs, we have found several systematic trends: i) the linewidths decrease with increasing energy of the upper energy level (Eupp) involved in the transition; ii) differences in the morphology of their emission, with the lines with lower Eupp being more spatially extended than those with higher Eupp; iii) the more luminous the source is, the broader the detected line. These trends are found over four orders of magnitude (10^3.5-10^7.5 Lsun), and seems to rule out gravitational collapse or keplerian rotation as the major kinematic ingredients in these regions. However, it could be explained by two other different mechanisms: I) the presence of a solid rigid disk; II) outflow activity. We propose to establish convincingly these general trends by observing for the first time the rotational emission from HC3N* from a sample of high mass star forming cores which cover uniformly IR luminosities from 10^4 to 10^6 Lsun.

fields.title: Triggering and Regulation of Extragalactic Star Formation
fields.abstract: We propose to use the W-band receiver on GBT to detect or place stringent upper limits on the emission from high density molecular gas tracing incipient star formation in J1023+1952, a putative newly formed dwarf galaxy in the interacting system Arp94. J1023 offers a unique laboratory in which to determine the processes that dominate the triggering and regulation of star formation. Despite being gas-rich, with HI/CO densities comparable in the north and south, it appears to have only recently begun to form stars in a highly localised ~2-kpc active star-forming ridge to the south.  Detection or otherwise of HCO+ 1-0 will determine whether there is new star formation occuring in the northern regions and detect any on-going star formation in the south.  Detections of HCO+ will be publishable and will form the basis of a future ALMA project.

fields.title: Probing the Evolution of Massive Dense  Cores
fields.abstract: We propose to observe a small sample of 19 massive cores identified in Spitzer infrared dark clouds (IRDCs) in the J=1-0 transitions of two deuterium containing molecular species. Observations of low mass dense cores have shown the deuterated species uniquely probe the coldest and densest regions of the cores, the regions where CO is frozen out on to the surface of dust grains. Chemical models have shown that these species reach peak abundance in the most evolved cores; those which are closest to gravitational collapse. Recent observations have also shown high levels of deuteration in cold cores associated with massive star formation and proposed that these species are also tracers of the evolution of these massive regions. We will use the observations proposed here to investigate the level of deuteration in massive, dense IRDC cores. This will allow us to both study the properties of the cold gas in these regions and  potentially identify those objects closest to collapsing to form a massive star.

fields.title: Carbon Radio Recombination Lines in HI Self-Absorbing Clouds
fields.abstract:
We propose to observe Carbon Radio Recombination Lines (CRRLs) on sightlines through three HI self-absorbing clouds in the Galaxy.  Our observations will build on a recent result (Roshi & Kantharia 2011) which used CRRLs measured at multiple frequecies in the Heeschen-Riegel-Crutcher HI self-absorbing region, in combination with the known HI properties of that cloud, to probe physical properties such as temperature and density, heating and cooling rates, and the molecular formation and dissociation rates.  The study concludes that the cloud is in the process of converting from atomic to molecular gas.  

We wish to expand the study to more clouds in the ISM.  We have chosen three sightlines with HI self-absorbing clouds, for which CRRL observations exist or have been approved at frequencies < 100 MHz.  These data will complement the proposed measurements made using the GBT PF1 receivers at UHF frequencies, allowing fitted models to be constrained over a range frequencies.  The proposed observations will thus provide a key piece of information for characterizing cold clouds and their molecular formation rates in the ISM.

fields.title: A Search for New Class II Methanol Maser Transitions
fields.abstract:
We propose to search for class II methanol maser emission 
in the 1_1 - 2_0 E and 7_2 - 8_1 A+ transitions, at 68.305 and 80.993
GHz.  Both of these transitions have been suggested as maser
candidates based on radiative pumping models.  The discovery of new
class II methanol maser transitions would provide useful constraints
on the pumping models for these transitions, and help to disentangle
the unusual behavior of various rare methanol maser species.

We have selected 16 high mass
star formation regions that we consider to be ideal-to-reasonable candidates
to search for maser emission.  We request up to 11 hours of GBT time to
observe some or all of these sources in search of maser emission.

fields.title: High-precision pulsar timing with the EVLA
fields.abstract:
Direct detection of gravitational waves (GW) is a major goal in experimental
physics and will revolutionize astrophysics, opening an entirely new spectrum
for exploration.  Precision pulsar timing stands an excellent chance of being
the first method to accomplish this feat.  Until now, pulsar timing has been
almost exclusively the domain of large single-dish radio telescopes.  Timing of
most millisecond pulsars is sensitivity limited and in the past, array
telescopes have typically not had competitive collecting areas or bandwidths
for this type of observing.  In this proposal we aim to build up the pulsar
timing capabilities of the EVLA and simultaneously push the boundaries of
high-precision timing.

fields.title: An HCN and HCO+ Map of M100: Testing the 4mm Receiver for Extragalactic Studies
fields.abstract: We propose shared risk observations using the 4-mm receiver to map the high density gas tracers HCN and HCO+ from the central 30$\arcsec$ of the nearby spiral M100 (NGC 4321). This bright, complex source will represent a good test of the ability of the 4-mm receiver to map faint spectral lines in extended objects. We have the data in-hand to verify its performance: lower resolution IRAM 30m mapping of HCN and HCO+, CO (2-1) mapping from the IRAM-30m, and archival 1-0 mapping. Further M100 is a target of ALMA science verification (and we have proposed to ALMA for high resolution HCN mapping), offering a possibility to demonstrate early synergy between these telescopes. Scientifically, high resolution maps of HCN and HCO+ will allow us to look for environmental drivers of enhanced dense gas fractions.

fields.title: Extended Timing of Some of the New Fermi MSPs
fields.abstract: We propose to continue timing four millisecond pulsars that were discovered in a GBT pulsar survey of faint Fermi gamma-ray sources. All four either have or will have good initial timing solutions and pulsed gamma-ray detections by the end of the current GBT observing semester, and so will not continue to be timed under the Fermi program. However, an additional 6 months of timing will provide constraints on the proper motion, needed to correct estimates of the spin down energy, and determine the feasibility of obtaining timing parallaxes. In addition, two of the pulsars are short orbit, black widow type systems which may exhibit orbital variations which can be used to study the mass distribution of their companions.

fields.title: The Pulsar Triple System in M4
fields.abstract: We request 12 45-minute epochs over the course of the next year to continue our monitoring of the millisecond pulsar B1620$-$26 in the globular cluster M4.  This pulsar is orbited every 191 days by a low-mass white dwarf and roughly every 40 years by a planet of about 0.5 Jupiter mass.  The goals of our long-term experiment are to fully characterize the dual Keplerian orbit, incorporating the planet's perturbative effects on the inner orbit.  Regular observations of the GBT will allow us to remain sensitive to both short- and long-term effects in this unique pulsar hierarchical triple system.

fields.title: Long Term Timing of 54 Recycled Pulsars in Bulge Globular Clusters
fields.abstract:
We propose to continue timing 54 recycled pulsars in the bulge
globular clusters Terzan 5, M28, NGC6440, and NGC6544 over the next
year using the coherent-filterbank mode of GUPPI at L-band.  Almost
all of these pulsars (48 of 54) were discovered with the GBT and many
of them are exotic or even unique pulsar systems.  They include 31
binary pulsars, 12 of which are in highly eccentric orbits and several
of which appear to be massive neutron stars.  There are at least 5
eclipsing systems, several of which are X-ray sources and one of which
contains the fastest rotating neutron star known.  Our proposed
observations, totalling 85 hours and including high quality
polarization measurements, will extend and improve our timing
solutions and allow new insights into pulsar astronomy, neutron star
physics, binary and globular cluster evolution, the interstellar
medium, the Galactic magnetic field, and globular cluster dynamics.

fields.title: Hunting for Terrestrial-mass Planets around the Millisecond Pulsar NGC 6440C
fields.abstract: We are requesting 30x2-hr observations spread over 60 days to search for terrestrial-mass planets around the globular cluster millisecond pulsar J1748-2021C, located in NGC 6440.  This pulsars exhibits uniquely large unmodeled systematic trends in its timing residuals which with timescales on the order of tens of days.  These strongly suggest the presence of one or more terrestrial-mass planets.  If confirmed, this would make NGC 6440C only the terrestrial-mass extrasolar planetary system known, and the first in a globular cluster.  This would shed light on a unique scenario for planet formation, particularly in the globular cluster environment.  We already have seen evidence for a 2.3 Mars mass planet, but this alone cannot explain the observed systematics.  Previous observations of this pulsar have proven insufficient for solving this mystery, and a renewed campaign with the GBT appears to be the best solution.

fields.title: New Millisecond Pulsars in Gamma-ray-detected Globular Clusters - copy
fields.abstract: Past searches for radio millisecond pulsars in globular clusters have been very successful, leading to the discoveries of 140 millisecond pulsars in 26 clusters.  Fifteen Fermi Gamma-ray Space Telescope sources have been associated with globular clusters, about half of which have gamma-ray luminosities and spectra consistent with an ensemble of millisecond pulsars.  No millisecond pulsars are known in 9 of these clusters, but are expected to be present and causing the gamma-ray emission.  Past searches of two of these clusters led to the discovery of one new millisecond pulsar, PSR J1835-3259; we propose observations to obtain a timing solution for this pulsar.  We also propose to search for millisecond pulsars in another globular cluster, 2MS-GC01.  We request 9 hours at C-band to search this cluster, and 19 hours at S- or L-band, spread over the course of one year to time the new pulsar, with the GUPPI pulsar backend.

fields.title: A Radar Mapping Search for Recent Volcanism on Venus
fields.abstract: Radar mapping using the Arecibo telescope in 1988 provided the first 2-km resolution Earth-based image of Venus [1,2] (Fig. 1). The Magellan mission, over the next several years, mapped almost the entire planet at a spatial resolution of about 100 m. At the next close approach in June 2012, we thus have a 24-year baseline to search for surface changes due to volcanic processes. We propose to use the Arecibo S-band transmitter and GBT receivers for six days near close approach, providing a map of the visible hemisphere with 1-km spatial resolution. The result will be a comparison between the 1988 and 2012 datasets, and Magellan data, to show any areas of possible change.
